const a = [
  {"id":5447,"text":"Which of the following statements is correct regarding the route of the great saphenous vein?","explanation":null,"reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 655.","responses":[{"text":"Joins the femoral vein superficial to the fascia lata","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior to the medial condyle of the tibia and femur","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Posterior to the medial malleolus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Passes up the lateral side of the leg","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior to the medial malleolus","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5511,"text":"Injury to which of the following nerve causes winging of the scapula?","explanation":null,"reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 179.","responses":[{"text":"Long thoracic nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Dorsal scapular nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medial pectoral nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nerve to subclavius","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral pectoral nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5518,"text":"A football player gets hit on the lateral aspect of his knee joint, resulting in a fracture of the neck of the fibula. Which of the following nerves is most likely to be injured in this case?","explanation":"In the case of a fracture of the **neck of the fibula**, the nerve most likely to be injured is the **common peroneal nerve** (also known as the common fibular nerve). This nerve wraps around the neck of the fibula and is susceptible to injury in fractures involving this area.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nThe superficial fibular nerve is a branch of the common peroneal nerve, that supplies the lateral compartment of the leg.\r\nThe sciatic nerve is a large nerve originating from the lumbar and sacral plexus and splits into the tibial and common peroneal nerves.\r\nThe deep fibular nerve is another branch of the common peroneal nerve, that supplies the anterior compartment of the leg.\r\nThe tibial nerve is a branch of the sciatic nerve, that supplies the posterior compartment of the leg.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 542.","responses":[{"text":"Deep fibular nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Common peroneal nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sciatic nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superficial fibular nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tibial nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5582,"text":"A 34-year-old man is brought to the emergency room with a stab wound injury in his axilla. A neurologic examination reveals the injury has caused the posterior cord of the brachial plexus to be damaged. Which of the following structures is most likely affected?","explanation":null,"reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 180-181, 193.","responses":[{"text":"Rhomboid major","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Deltoid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Supraspinatus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pectoralis major","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Subclavius","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5792,"text":"Which of the following signifies the action of Botulinum toxin?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 96.","responses":[{"text":"Breaks down the acetylcholine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blocks the release of acetylcholine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Increases the release of acetylcholine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreases the formation of acetylcholine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blocks the uptake of acetylcholine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":6045,"text":"Which of the following is the active metabolite of vitamin D?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020. 390.","responses":[{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"1-hydroxyvitamin D3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"1,25-dihydrocholecalciferol","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"7-dehydrocholesterol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"25-hydroxyvitamin D3","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9107,"text":"A gunshot wound at the axilla severely injures the posterior cord of the brachial plexus. Which of the following muscles would be affected?","explanation":"A gunshot wound at the axilla that severely injures the **posterior cord** of the brachial plexus would affect the **deltoid muscle**. The posterior cord gives rise to the axillary nerve, which innervates the deltoid muscle. Damage to the posterior cord would, therefore, impair the function of the deltoid, affecting arm abduction among other movements.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nThe pronator teres muscle is innervated by the median nerve, which is not a branch of the posterior cord of the brachial plexus.\r\n\r\nThe subclavius muscle is innervated by the nerve to the subclavius, which comes from the superior trunk of the brachial plexus.\r\n\r\nThe bicep brachii muscle is primarily innervated by the musculocutaneous nerve, which is a branch of the lateral cord of the brachial plexus.\r\n\r\nThe rhomboid major muscle is innervated by the dorsal scapular nerve, which is a branch of the cervical spinal nerves and not part of the brachial plexus.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 180-181, 193.","responses":[{"text":"Pronator teres","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Deltoid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Bicep brachii","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rhomboid major","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Subclavius","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9262,"text":"Which of the following features of compact bone is different from that of a spongy bone?","explanation":"The feature of **compact bone** that is different from that of spongy bone is that **it has a Haversian system**. Compact bone is organized into **osteons** or Haversian systems, which are a characteristic not found in spongy bone.\r\n\r\nThe thoracic skeleton is made up of various types of bones that include both compact and spongy bones. The term \"cancellous bone\" actually refers to spongy bone, not compact bone. Cranial bones are also made up of both types of bone. Lining the medullary cavity is a specific feature of compact bone, but it does not distinguish it from spongy bone.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 145-146.","responses":[{"text":"Lines medullary cavity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It has a Haversian system","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Thoracic skeleton is made up from this","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cranial bones are made up from this","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is also called cancellous bone","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9289,"text":"For routine blood sample collection of a patient, the nurse selects a vein present superficially, in the subcutaneous tissue overlying the cubital fossa, in front of the bicipital aponeurosis. Which of the following vein is being used for venipuncture?","explanation":"The **median cubital vein** is the vein being used for blood sample collection in this patient and is superficially located in the subcutaneous tissue overlying the cubital fossa and in front of the **bicipital aponeurosis**. This vein is often chosen due to its superficial location and the ease of venipuncture.\r\n\r\nThe cephalic vein is located laterally in the arm and does not cross the cubital fossa. The axillary vein is much higher in the arm, located in the axilla (armpit), and is not used for routine venipuncture. The median vein is more distal and not typically used for routine venipuncture. The basilic vein is found medially and also does not cross the cubital fossa.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 209, 214.","responses":[{"text":"Cephalic vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Median cubital vein","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Basilic vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Median vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Axillary vein","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9330,"text":"A female patient is brought to the emergency department. X-ray findings show a fracture of the femoral neck and avascular necrosis of the femoral head. This is most likely a consequence of interruption to the blood supply to the head of the femur. What is the source of blood supply to the femoral head?","explanation":"The primary source of blood supply to the femoral head is the **branches from the profunda femoris artery**. These are the **medial and lateral circumflex femoral arteries**, and they play a critical role in supplying the head and neck of the femur. Interruption to these vessels can lead to avascular necrosis of the femoral head, a serious condition that requires prompt management.\r\n\r\nThe obturator artery primarily supplies the adductor muscles and does not significantly contribute to the blood supply of the femoral head. \r\n\r\nThe femoral artery itself gives off the profunda femoris but doesn't directly supply the femoral head. \r\n\r\nThe Inferior gluteal artery supplies the gluteus maximus and is not a main supplier to the femoral head. \r\n\r\nThe tibial artery is involved in the lower leg and does not supply the femoral head.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 791.","responses":[{"text":"Tibial artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Branches from the profunda femoris artery","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Femoral artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Obturator artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior gluteal artery","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9333,"text":"A person is having pain and tenderness in the left ankle joint. Which structure is most likely to be ruptured?","explanation":"The **lateral ligament** is most likely to be ruptured. The lateral ligament complex of the ankle, which includes the anterior talofibular ligament, the calcaneofibular ligament, and the posterior talofibular ligament, is commonly injured in ankle sprains. These usually occur due to inversion injuries where the sole of the foot turns inward.\r\n\r\nThe medial ligament, also known as the deltoid ligament, is much stronger and less commonly injured than the lateral ligament. The posterior cruciate ligament and the anterior cruciate ligament are ligaments within the knee joint, not the ankle. Thus, they would not be implicated in ankle pain and tenderness.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 825.","responses":[{"text":"Deltoid ligament","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior cruciate ligament","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral ligament","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Medial ligament","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Posterior cruciate ligament","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12657,"text":"What is the mode of spread of snake venom within the human body?","explanation":"Snake venom is primarily spread within the human body through the **lymphatic system**.\r\n\r\nWhen a snake injects venom into a human through a bite, the venom enters the surrounding tissues. From there, it can be absorbed into the lymphatic vessels, which are part of the immune system and responsible for fluid drainage and immune surveillance.\r\n\r\nThe lymphatic vessels transport the venomous components along with other fluid and waste products to the lymph nodes. In the lymph nodes, the venom can interact with immune cells and trigger an immune response.\r\n\r\nUnlike the systemic circulation of blood through arteries and veins, the lymphatic system has a slower flow rate. This allows the venom to spread gradually and affect lymph nodes and surrounding tissues.\r\n\r\nAlthough snake venom can potentially enter the systemic circulation through blood vessels, the primary mode of spread within the human body is through the lymphatic system.","reference":"Park K. Park’s Textbook of Preventive and Social Medicine. 25th ed. Bhanot Publishers; 2019: 443.","responses":[{"text":"Respiratory","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arterial","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Venous","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cardiac circulation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymphatic","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12702,"text":"Which of the following muscles of the thigh is supplied by two nerves?","explanation":"The **adductor magnus** muscle is unique because it is innervated by both the **obturator nerve** and the **sciatic nerve**. The hamstring part of the adductor magnus is innervated by the sciatic nerve, while the adductor part is innervated by the obturator nerve. This dual innervation allows the muscle to participate in multiple actions such as adduction and extension of the thigh.\r\n\r\nGracilis, obturator externus, adductor brevis, and adductor longus are primarily innervated by the obturator nerve and are not known for receiving dual innervation.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 586.","responses":[{"text":"Adductor longus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adductor magnus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Adductor brevis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gracilis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Obturator externus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12704,"text":"Which of the following muscles is partially paralyzed when the obturator nerve is injured?","explanation":"The **adductor magnus** is a large muscle in the inner thigh that is responsible for adducting, or bringing together the thigh. This muscle is unique because it receives innervation from both the **obturator nerve** and the **sciatic nerve**. The hamstring part of the adductor magnus is innervated by the sciatic nerve, whereas the adductor part is innervated by the obturator nerve. Therefore, if the obturator nerve is injured, the adductor part of the adductor magnus will be affected, resulting in partial paralysis of the muscle.\r\n\r\nAdductor longus, gracilis, obturator externus, and adductor brevis are primarily or entirely innervated by the obturator nerve, and would therefore be more significantly affected in case of an injury to this nerve.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 586.","responses":[{"text":"Adductor longus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Obturator externus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adductor magnus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Gracilis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adductor brevis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12705,"text":"Which of the following bones is not a part of the medial longitudinal arch of the foot?","explanation":"The **cuboid** is not a part of the **medial longitudinal arch of the foot**. The medial longitudinal arch is primarily formed by the **calcaneus, talus, navicular**, and the **first three metatarsals**. These bones work together with various ligaments and muscles to provide the arch-like shape of the medial aspect of the foot, which plays an essential role in absorbing shock and providing flexibility during walking and running.\r\n\r\nThe cuboid, on the other hand, is a component of the **lateral longitudinal arch of the foot**, along with the fourth and fifth metatarsals.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 814.","responses":[{"text":"Calcaneus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Navicular","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Talus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"1-3 metatarsals","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cuboid","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12706,"text":"Which of the following muscles does not provide ligamentous support to the lateral longitudinal arch?","explanation":"The muscle that does not provide ligamentous support to the lateral longitudinal arch is the **tibialis anterior**. The tibialis anterior mainly supports the **medial longitudinal arch** of the foot and is responsible for **dorsiflexion and inversion** of the foot.\r\n\r\nPeroneus brevis, peroneus tertius, abductor digiti minimi, and peroneus longus are all muscles that provide some level of support to the lateral longitudinal arch. These muscles play a role in various movements like eversion, plantarflexion, and abduction of the foot, thereby contributing to the stability of the lateral arch.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 625.","responses":[{"text":"Peroneus brevis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Abductor digiti minimi","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Peroneus tertius","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tibialis anterior","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Peroneus longus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12707,"text":"The medial and lateral menisci of the knee are composed of which of the following type of cartilage?","explanation":"The **medial and lateral menisci** of the knee are composed of **fibrocartilage**. Fibrocartilage is a type of cartilage that is particularly rich in collagen fibers, providing it with added strength and making it ideal for withstanding mechanical stress. This type of cartilage is crucial in the knee joint, as it acts as a cushion and provides a stabilizing function during weight-bearing activities, like walking or running.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nHyaline cartilage is a different type of cartilage found in areas like the respiratory tract and the ends of long bones. Elastic cartilage is more commonly found in structures that require more flexibility, like the ear. The synovial membrane is not a type of cartilage but is part of the synovial joints, contributing to the production of synovial fluid for joint lubrication.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 801.","responses":[{"text":"Fibro-elastic cartilage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyaline cartilage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrocartilage","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Elastic cartilage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Synovial membrane","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12708,"text":"The knee/patellar reflex is absent upon injury of which of the following nerves?","explanation":"The **absence of the knee/patellar reflex** is indicative of an injury to the **femoral nerve**. This nerve provides motor innervation to the **quadriceps femoris**, a muscle crucial for leg extension and thus involved in the knee-jerk reflex. It is also responsible for the sensory innervation of the skin over the anterior and medial thigh and the medial leg. It also\r\n\r\nThe sciatic nerve primarily serves the posterior thigh and leg and is not directly involved in the knee-jerk reflex. The tibial nerve, a branch of the sciatic nerve, primarily innervates the muscles of the posterior leg and also does not play a role in the knee-jerk reflex. The obturator nerve is mostly involved with the adductor muscles of the thigh and is not associated with this reflex. The peroneal nerve, another branch of the sciatic nerve, serves the anterior and lateral compartments of the leg and the dorsum of the foot, but it also is not involved in the knee-jerk reflex.","reference":"Refai NA, Tadi P. Anatomy, bony pelvis and lower limb, thigh femoral nerve. StatPearls. Published 2022. Accessed November 26, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK556065/","responses":[{"text":"Sciatic nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tibial nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Femoral nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Obturator nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Peroneal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12709,"text":"Which of the following ligaments of the hip joint lies is an intracapsular ligament?","explanation":"The **ligamentum teres** is an intracapsular ligament of the hip joint. This ligament is unique because it is one of the few that are actually inside the joint capsule. It runs from the acetabulum in the pelvis to the fovea of the head of the femur. Although its role in adult hip stability is minimal, it does contain a small artery that can supply blood to the head of the femur, particularly during the developmental years. \r\n\r\nThe **pubofemoral ligament, ischiofemoral ligament**, and **iliofemoral ligament** are all **extracapsular ligaments**. They are situated outside the joint capsule and contribute to the stability of the hip joint by limiting its range of motion.\r\n\r\nThe fibrous capsule is not a ligament per se; rather, it is the tough, fibrous membrane that encloses the hip joint and is lined by synovial membrane from the inside. It works in concert with the ligaments to stabilize the hip joint but is not classified as an intracapsular ligament.","reference":"Gold M, Munjal A, Varacallo M. Anatomy, bony pelvis and lower limb, hip joint. StatPearls. Published 2022. Accessed November 26, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470555/","responses":[{"text":"Fibrous capsule","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ischiofemoral ligament","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iliofemoral ligament","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ligamentum teres","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pubofemoral ligament","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12710,"text":"The external iliac artery continues as the femoral artery when it passes underneath the inguinal ligament at what point?","explanation":"The external iliac artery continues as the **femoral artery** when it passes underneath the inguinal ligament at the **mid-inguinal point**.\r\n\r\nThe mid-inguinal point is defined as the point midway between the **anterior superior iliac spine** and the **pubic symphysis**. This is the location where the external iliac artery transitions into the femoral artery as it passes under the inguinal ligament. This anatomical landmark is crucial for various procedures, such as arterial catheterization, and is essential for a medical professional to know for diagnostic and therapeutic purposes.","reference":"(1) Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 713.\r\n\r\n(2) Sugumar K, Gupta M. Anatomy, abdomen and pelvis, inguinal (Crural, pouparts) ligament. StatPearls. Published 2022. Accessed November 26, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK542321/","responses":[{"text":"1 cm medial to the mid-inguinal point","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"1 cm lateral to the mid-inguinal point","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mid-inguinal point","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"2 cm medial to mid-inguinal point","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2 cm lateral to the mid-inguinal point","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12711,"text":"Which of the following arteries is not involved in the formation of trochanteric anastomosis?","explanation":"The artery not involved in the formation of the trochanteric anastomosis is the **obturator artery**.\r\n\r\nThe **trochanteric anastomosis** is an important arterial circle at the hip joint region, especially around the greater trochanter. It is mainly formed by the **superior gluteal artery, medial circumflex femoral artery, lateral circumflex femoral artery**, and **inferior gluteal artery**. These arteries provide a rich blood supply to the head and neck of the femur, and their anastomosis serves as collateral circulation, especially important in cases of arterial obstruction. \r\n\r\nThe Obturator artery is generally not a part of this anastomosis, as it primarily supplies the adductor muscles of the thigh and the hip joint but does not significantly contribute to the blood supply of the head and neck of the femur involved in the trochanteric anastomosis.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 594.","responses":[{"text":"Inferior gluteal artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral circumflex femoral artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior gluteal artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Obturator artery","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Medial circumflex femoral artery","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12713,"text":"A patient is unable to flex the toes and his foot remains everted and dorsiflexed. Which of the following nerves is injured in this case?","explanation":"The nerve likely to be injured in a patient who is unable to **flex the toes** and whose foot **remains everted and dorsiflexed** is the **tibial nerve**.\r\n\r\nThe tibial nerve is a branch of the sciatic nerve and it primarily controls the muscles of the posterior compartment of the leg, which are involved in plantar flexion of the foot and flexion of the toes.\r\n\r\nThe common peroneal nerve mainly controls dorsiflexion and eversion but would not affect toe flexion to the same degree. The superficial peroneal nerve and deep peroneal nerve are branches of the common peroneal nerve and are primarily involved in eversion and dorsiflexion, respectively. There is no medial peroneal nerve; it is commonly referred to as the common peroneal nerve.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 764.","responses":[{"text":"Medial peroneal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Deep peroneal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tibial nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Common peroneal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superficial peroneal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12714,"text":"Which of the following muscles of the lower limb is involved in flexion at both the hip and the knee joint?","explanation":"The muscle involved in flexion at both the hip and the knee joint is the **sartorius**. \r\n\r\nSartorius is the longest muscle in the human body and spans **both the hip and knee joints**. It originates from the anterior superior iliac spine and inserts into the medial side of the tibia. It acts to flex, abduct, and laterally rotate the thigh at the hip joint, and also to flex the leg at the knee joint. \r\n\r\nGluteus maximus is mainly involved in extending and laterally rotating the hip. The iliacus is a flexor of the hip. The rectus femoris is a part of the quadriceps muscle group and acts to extend the knee and flex the hip. The biceps femoris is part of the hamstrings group and is involved in flexion at the knee and extension at the hip, but not flexion at the hip.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 582.","responses":[{"text":"Biceps femoris","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rectus femoris","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iliacus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sartorius","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Gluteus maximus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12715,"text":"Which of the following statements regarding the femoral nerve is incorrect?","explanation":"In addition to the saphenous nerve, the **femoral nerve** also gives off anterior cutaneous branches, which supply the skin over the **anterior and medial aspects of the thigh**.\r\n\r\nThe femoral nerve is indeed formed from the anterior divisions of the anterior primary rami of L2, L3, and L4 spinal nerves. It does lie outside the femoral sheath, and it divides into multiple branches after it passes through the femoral triangle. The femoral and obturator nerves are both formed from spinal segments L2, L3, and L4.","reference":"(1) Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 710.\r\n\r\n(2) Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 401.","responses":[{"text":"It has no cutaneous branch other than the saphenous nerve.","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"It divides after passing through the femoral triangle.","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is formed from the anterior divisions of anterior primary rami of L2, L3, L4.","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is formed from the same spinal segments as the obturator nerve.","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It lies outside the femoral sheath.","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12716,"text":"Which of the muscles and innervating nerves is correctly paired?","explanation":"The **adductor longus** is primarily innervated by the **obturator nerve**. It is one of the muscles responsible for adducting the thigh and is part of the medial compartment of the thigh.\r\n\r\nThe adductor brevis is also primarily innervated by the obturator nerve, not the femoral nerve. Adductor magnus is mainly supplied by the obturator nerve and partly by the sciatic nerve, not the saphenous or femoral nerves. The adductor longus is not innervated by the sciatic nerve; it is innervated by the obturator nerve.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 586.","responses":[{"text":"Adductor magnus, femoral nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adductor longus, obturator nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Adductor longus, sciatic nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adductor brevis, femoral nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adductor magnus, saphenous nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12718,"text":"Which of the following statements best describes coxa valga?","explanation":"In **coxa valga**, the angle between the **neck of the femur** and the **femoral shaft** is greater than the normal range, which is generally around 125-135 degrees in adults. This condition can lead to various biomechanical changes and may be associated with hip joint instability or increased stress on the joint.\r\n\r\nFracture of the neck of the femur, avascular necrosis of the head of the femur, and fracture of the greater trochanter are specific pathological conditions affecting the hip joint but do not describe coxa valga. \r\n\r\nDecreased angle of inclination between the neck of femur and lesser trochanter actually describes coxa vara, which is the opposite of coxa valga.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 685.","responses":[{"text":"Decreased angle of inclination between neck of femur and lesser trochanter","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased angle of inclination between neck of femur and shaft","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Avascular necrosis of the head of femur","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fracture of greater trochanter","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fracture of neck of femur","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12740,"text":"The medial malleolus is formed by which of the following structures?","explanation":"The **medial malleolus** is formed by the **lower medial end of the tibia**. This bony prominence can be easily palpated on the inner side of the ankle and serves as an attachment point for ligaments stabilizing the ankle joint.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nThe tibiofibular joint is a joint between the tibia and fibula, and it does not form the medial malleolus. The lower lateral end of the fibula forms the lateral malleolus, not the medial one. The calcaneus is the heel bone and is not involved in forming the medial malleolus. The talus is a tarsal bone that articulates with the tibia and fibula but does not form the medial malleolus.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 612.","responses":[{"text":"Lower medial end of tibia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Talus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lower lateral end of fibula","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcaneus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tibiofibular joint","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12743,"text":"The apex of the plantar aponeurosis is attached to which of the following structures?","explanation":"The apex of the plantar aponeurosis is attached to the **medial and lateral tubercles of the calcaneus**. This fibrous structure serves as a supportive mechanism for the arch of the foot and provides a foundation for the muscles that allow for movement of the toes and foot.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nThe fibrous flexor sheath is related to the flexor tendons in the fingers and toes but is not the attachment point for the apex of the plantar aponeurosis. The talus is a tarsal bone that articulates with the calcaneus but is not the attachment site. The deep transverse ligament connects the metatarsal heads but is not involved with the plantar aponeurosis. The medial malleolus is part of the tibia and is also not the attachment site for the plantar aponeurosis.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 645.","responses":[{"text":"Talus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medial malleolus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medial and lateral tubercles of the calcaneus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrous flexor sheath","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Deep transverse ligament","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12744,"text":"A 17-year-old patient presents to the outpatient department with a sub-glenoid shoulder dislocation. Which of the following nerves is at risk of injury due to its close relation inferior to this joint capsule?","explanation":"The **axillary nerve** is most at risk of injury in the case of a **sub-glenoid shoulder dislocation** due to its close anatomical relationship inferior to the glenohumeral joint capsule. This nerve is responsible for innervating the deltoid and teres minor muscles and providing cutaneous sensation to the skin overlying the deltoid.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nThe radial nerve is not closely associated with the glenohumeral joint and is more prone to injury in humeral fractures. The ulnar nerve is also not closely related to this joint; it runs more distally in the arm. The median nerve is primarily involved in the forearm and hand and is not closely related to the shoulder joint. The musculocutaneous nerve is also not at immediate risk in a sub-glenoid dislocation; it innervates muscles in the anterior compartment of the arm.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 700.","responses":[{"text":"Ulnar nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Musculocutaneous nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Median nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Axillary nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Radial nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12802,"text":"Which of the following muscle's functioning is affected when the ulnar nerve is injured due to a wrist fracture?","explanation":"The functioning of the **adductor pollicis** muscle is most likely to be affected when the ulnar nerve is injured due to a **wrist fracture**. The adductor pollicis is responsible for adducting the thumb and is innervated by the ulnar nerve.\r\n\r\nThe abductor pollicis longus is innervated by the radial nerve and is primarily responsible for abducting the thumb. The flexor pollicis brevis has two heads; the superficial head is innervated by the median nerve and the deep head by the ulnar nerve. However, the median nerve plays a dominant role for this muscle. The flexor pollicis longus is responsible for flexing the thumb and is innervated by the anterior interosseous nerve, a branch of the median nerve. The lateral two lumbricals flex the metacarpophalangeal joints and extend the interphalangeal joints of the 2nd and 3rd digits and are mainly supplied by the median nerve.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 771, 780, 799.","responses":[{"text":"Adductor pollicis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Flexor pollicis longus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Flexor pollicis brevis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Abductor pollicis longus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral two lumbricals","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12803,"text":"A 16-year-old boy got injured during a soccer match and cannot flex his fingers. Which of the following muscles functioning is compromised in this case?","explanation":"The functioning of the **flexor digitorum profundus** is most likely compromised in this patient who cannot flex his fingers. This muscle is responsible for **flexing the distal interphalangeal joints** of the fingers, and it is innervated by both the median and ulnar nerves. \r\n\r\nThe palmaris longus is primarily involved in wrist flexion and is innervated by the median nerve. The flexor pollicis longus is responsible for thumb flexion and is innervated by the anterior interosseous nerve, a branch of the median nerve. The flexor carpi ulnaris flexes and adducts the wrist and is innervated by the ulnar nerve. The flexor carpi radialis, which is also involved in wrist flexion and radial abduction, is innervated by the median nerve.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 767, 771.","responses":[{"text":"Flexor carpi radialis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Palmaris longus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Flexor digitorum profundus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Flexor pollicis longus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Flexor carpi ulnaris","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12804,"text":"A 14-year-old boy got hit by a ball on his medial epicondyle during a baseball match. He cannot perform flexion and adduction at his wrist joint. Which of the following muscles is most likely affected in this case?","explanation":"The **flexor carpi ulnaris** muscle is responsible for **flexion and adduction at the wrist joint** and is innervated by the ulnar nerve, which passes near the medial epicondyle. An injury to the **medial epicondyle** could potentially affect the ulnar nerve and subsequently impact the function of the flexor carpi ulnaris muscle.\r\n\r\nThe palmaris longus, which is mainly responsible for flexing the wrist, is innervated by the median nerve and is not likely to be affected by an injury to the medial epicondyle. The flexor carpi radialis, also a wrist flexor, is innervated by the median nerve as well. Flexor digitorum superficialis, responsible for flexing the middle phalanges of the four fingers, and flexor digitorum profundus, which flexes the distal phalanges, are innervated by the median nerve and, to some extent, the ulnar nerve but are less likely to be involved in this specific case focusing on wrist flexion and adduction.","reference":"(1) Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 767.\r\n\r\n(2) Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 239.","responses":[{"text":"Palmaris longus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Flexor digitorum superficialis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Flexor carpi ulnaris","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Flexor carpi radialis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Flexor digitorum profundus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12805,"text":"A medical student is asked to demonstrate the biceps reflex in a ward test. A normal response of involuntary contraction of the biceps brachii is observed. The integrity of which of the following nerves is confirmed by this reflex?","explanation":"The integrity of the **musculocutaneous nerve** is confirmed by a **normal biceps reflex**. This nerve arises from the lateral cord of the brachial plexus and is responsible for innervating the biceps brachii muscle. A normal biceps reflex indicates that the musculocutaneous nerve and its associated **spinal cord levels (C5-C6)** are functioning properly.\r\n\r\nThe median nerve is not tested by the biceps reflex; it mainly innervates the muscles in the anterior compartment of the forearm and some muscles in the hand. The axillary nerve is responsible for innervating the deltoid and teres minor muscles and is not involved in the biceps reflex. The ulnar nerve innervates most of the intrinsic muscles of the hand and some muscles in the forearm but is not responsible for the biceps reflex. The radial nerve innervates the triceps brachii and the extensor muscles in the posterior compartment of the forearm and is also not involved in the biceps reflex.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 211.","responses":[{"text":"Ulnar nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Radial nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Median nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Musculocutaneous nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Axillary nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12806,"text":"A swimmer visits the orthopedic department with a complaint of sudden pain in his upper arm. During the physical examination, the intertubercular sulcus (bicipital groove) is palpated by the doctor by keeping his fingers on the greater and lesser tubercles of the humerus. Which of the following structures passes through this sulcus?","explanation":"The structure that passes through the **intertubercular sulcus** (bicipital groove) is the **long head of the biceps brachii**. This sulcus is located between the greater and lesser tubercles of the humerus and serves as a groove for the tendon of the long head of the biceps brachii muscle. This structure is often assessed in cases of shoulder and upper arm pain.\r\n\r\nThe subscapularis tendon is not located in the intertubercular sulcus; rather, it attaches to the lesser tubercle of the humerus. The axillary artery is a major blood vessel but does not pass through the intertubercular sulcus; it travels in the axillary region. The short head of the biceps brachii attaches to the coracoid process of the scapula and does not pass through the intertubercular sulcus. Similarly, the axillary nerve does not pass through this sulcus; it courses through the axillary region supplying the deltoid and teres minor muscles.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 146.","responses":[{"text":"Axillary nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Axillary artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Subscapularis tendon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The long head of biceps brachii","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Short head of biceps brachii","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12807,"text":"A 56-year-old woman visits the neurology outpatient clinic with complaints of burning pain and pins and needles sensation on lateral three and a half fingers. Upon examination, the physician also observes weakness of the thenar muscles. What is the most likely diagnosis in this case?","explanation":"**Carpal tunnel syndrome** is characterized by **burning pain, tingling**, and **numbness** in the distribution of the median nerve, which includes the **lateral three and a half fingers**. Additionally, the median nerve innervates the thenar muscles, and its compression in carpal tunnel syndrome can result in **thenar muscle weakness**.\r\n\r\nTensynovitis typically involves inflammation of the tendon sheath and would not typically affect sensory nerves or thenar muscles. Tennis elbow, or lateral epicondylitis, is a condition affecting the lateral elbow and would not present with symptoms in the fingers or thenar muscle weakness. Trigger finger is a condition involving the locking or snapping of a finger and would not affect multiple fingers or thenar muscles. Dupuytren contracture involves a fibromatosis of palmar fascia leading to flexion deformities of the fingers but does not affect sensory nerves or thenar muscles.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 260.","responses":[{"text":"Carpal tunnel syndrome","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Trigger finger","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tensynovitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dupuytren contracture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tennis elbow","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12808,"text":"A 50-year-old man presents to the outpatient department and complains that his 2nd and 3rd digits remain partially extended when he tries to make a fist. Which of the following nerves is most likely damaged in this case?","explanation":"The most likely damaged nerve in this patient is the **median nerve**. It innervates most of the flexor muscles in the forearm and some muscles in the hand, affecting the ability to flex the **2nd and 3rd digits**. \r\n\r\nThe musculocutaneous nerve mainly supplies the muscles in the anterior compartment of the arm and wouldn't affect the digits. The axillary nerve primarily innervates the deltoid and teres minor muscles, so it wouldn't be involved in digit flexion. Radial nerve damage typically causes \"wrist drop\" and primarily affects extensor muscles. Ulnar nerve damage would more commonly cause \"claw hand\" affecting the 4th and 5th digits.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 260.","responses":[{"text":"Musculocutaneous nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Axillary nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Radial nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ulnar nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Median nerve","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12809,"text":"A 45-year-old man who uses crutches to walk because of a foot fracture was referred to a neurologist, who observes that his wrist hangs limply. The patient was also unable to raise his arm. Further examination reveals that grip strength is unaffected but there is decreased sense of sensation on the posterior aspect of the affected arm. Which of the following nerve is most likely injured in this case?","explanation":"The most likely injured nerve in this 45-year-old man is the **radial nerve**. The clinical features of **\"wrist drop,\" decreased sensation in the posterior aspect of the arm**, and **inability to raise the arm** are all indicative of radial nerve injury. The radial nerve is particularly vulnerable in individuals who use **crutches** improperly, as pressure against the axilla can compress the nerve. The fact that the grip strength is unaffected might suggest that the injury is localized at the axilla or above, sparing the branches of the radial nerve that innervate the flexor muscles of the fingers and hand.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nSciatic nerve injury would lead to issues in the lower extremity, not the arm.\r\n\r\nMedian nerve injury would most likely present with symptoms affecting the palmar aspect of the first three and a half fingers and would not usually result in wrist drop or decreased sensation on the posterior aspect of the arm.\r\n\r\nAxillary nerve injury would affect the deltoid muscle and cutaneous sensation over the lateral aspect of the arm. It would not cause wrist drop or issues with grip strength.\r\n\r\nFemoral nerve injury would affect the lower extremity, specifically causing issues with hip flexion and knee extension, and has no relevance to the arm symptoms described.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 213, 231.","responses":[{"text":"Femoral nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Median nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Radial nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sciatic nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Axillary nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12832,"text":"Which of the following muscles is most likely to be affected in case of radial neuropathy at the axilla?","explanation":"The muscle most likely to be affected as a result of **radial neuropathy** is the **brachioradialis**. This muscle is specifically innervated by the radial nerve and is involved in the flexion of the forearm at the elbow.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nThe vastus medialis is in the thigh and is not affected by radial neuropathy, as it is innervated by the femoral nerve.\r\n\r\nThe biceps femoris muscle is part of the hamstring group in the thigh and is innervated by the sciatic nerve, not the radial nerve.\r\n\r\nThe deltoid muscle is innervated by the axillary nerve, not the radial nerve.\r\n \r\nThe flexor digitorum superficialis muscle is primarily innervated by the median nerve, not the radial nerve, and is responsible for flexing the digits.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 213, 221.","responses":[{"text":"Deltoid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vastus medialis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Flexor digitorum superficialis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Biceps femoris","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Brachioradialis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12833,"text":"What are the nerve root values of the radial nerve?","explanation":"The nerve root values for the radial nerve are **C5 to C8/T1**. This means the **radial nerve** is derived from the anterior rami of the fifth, sixth, seventh, and eighth cervical nerves and sometimes the first thoracic nerve (T1).\r\n\r\n- L2 to L4 and L4 to S3 roots pertain to lumbar and sacral plexuses and are unrelated to the radial nerve, part of the brachial plexus originating from the cervical spine.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 193.","responses":[{"text":"L2 to L4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"L4 to S3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C5 to C8/T1","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"C5, C6","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C6 to T1","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12834,"text":"What is the most common site of injury of the radial nerve?","explanation":"The most common site of injury to the **radial nerve** is the **spiral groove of the humerus**. This area is vulnerable because the nerve wraps around the **midshaft of the humerus** in this groove, exposing it to injury, especially in cases of humeral shaft fractures.\r\n\r\nThe intertrochanteric crest is a feature of the femur, not the humerus, and is therefore not related to radial nerve injury.\r\n  \r\nThe bicipital groove and the intertubercular sulcus are the same structure under different names and are involved in housing the long head of the biceps brachii tendon. The radial nerve does not pass through this sulcus.\r\n  \r\nThe medial supracondylar ridge is situated near the elbow on the medial side of the humerus. The radial nerve does not typically get injured at this site.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 809.","responses":[{"text":"Medial supracondylar ridge","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spiral groove of humerus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Intertubercular sulcus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bicipital groove","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intertrochanteric crest","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12835,"text":"An 18-year-old female attempted suicide by hanging. She used a rope and jumped with it around her neck from a significant height to cause injury resulting in damage to the nerves in the neck. The affected nerve plexus is formed by the union of the anterior rami of which of the following spinal nerves?","explanation":"The **brachial plexus**, formed by the anterior rami of **C5 to T1 spinal nerves**, would most likely be affected in this patient due to a significant hanging injury. This is because a violent force on the neck can potentially stretch or tear the nerves that form the brachial plexus, which is closely related to the neck structures.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nThe C2 to C6 nerves primarily contribute to the cervical plexus, which supplies the neck region but is less likely to be injured in this case.\r\n\r\nThe C7 to T3 nerves involve the lower part of the brachial plexus and upper thoracic nerves, which are not the primary concerns in a hanging injury.\r\n\r\nC8 to T4 nerves are mostly involved in the formation of thoracic and lumbar nerves, which wouldn't be directly affected by a hanging injury involving the neck.\r\n\r\nC3 to C7 nerves include the cervical plexus and the upper portion of the brachial plexus. Although they are near the neck, they are not the primary nerves affected in a significant hanging injury.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 189.","responses":[{"text":"C8 to T4 nerves","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C3 to C7 nerves","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C5 to T1 nerves","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"C7 to T3 nerves","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C2 to C6 nerves","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12838,"text":"While retaliating in a street crime robbery, a man got a deep cut from a knife to the posterior aspect of his arm, leading to nerve damage and weakening the muscles of the posterior compartment of the arm. Which of the following nerves is most likely to be the injured nerve?","explanation":"The nerve most likely to be injured due to a deep cut to the posterior aspect of the arm would be the **radial nerve**. The radial nerve innervates the muscles of the **posterior compartment of the arm and forearm**, and it runs along the posterior aspect of the arm. Injury to this nerve would result in the weakening of the muscles in the posterior compartment of the arm, consistent with the patient's symptoms.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nThe musculocutaneous nerve mainly innervates muscles in the anterior compartment of the arm and would not be affected by an injury to the posterior aspect. The axillary nerve innervates the deltoid and teres minor muscles and is not located in the posterior compartment of the arm. The ulnar nerve runs more medially and innervates muscles mainly in the forearm and hand; it would also not be affected by a cut to the posterior aspect of the arm. The median nerve primarily innervates muscles in the anterior compartment of the forearm and some muscles in the hand; it would not be impacted by an injury to the posterior aspect of the arm.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 207.","responses":[{"text":"Radial nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Axillary nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Median nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ulnar nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Musculocutaneous nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12840,"text":"The weight of the upper limb is transmitted to the sternum via the clavicle through the coracoclavicular ligament. This ligament has its attachment at what part of the clavicle?","explanation":"The weight of the upper limb is transmitted to the sternum via the clavicle through the **coracoclavicular ligament**. The correct attachment sites for this ligament on the clavicle are the **conoid tubercle and trapezoid ridge**.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nSubclavius and costal grooves are not the attachment sites for the coracoclavicular ligament. The anterior and posterior ends of the clavicle also do not serve as attachment sites for this ligament. Coastal tubercles are not an anatomical structure related to the clavicle. There is no costal ridge on the clavicle that is involved in the attachment of this ligament.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 143.","responses":[{"text":"Conoid tubercle and trapezoid ridge","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Costal and trapezoid ridges","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior and posterior ends","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Subclavius and costal grooves","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Conoid and coastal tubercles","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12842,"text":"A 63-year-old woman develops carcinoma in the outer lateral quadrant of the breast. Which of the following group of lymph nodes is most likely to be affected first?","explanation":"The **pectoral group of lymph nodes** (also known as the anterior or pectoral nodes) are most likely to be affected first in a carcinoma developing in the outer lateral quadrant of the breast. These nodes are situated along the lateral thoracic wall and primarily drain the breast. \r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nHumeral nodes primarily drain the upper limb and would not be the first group to be affected. Apical nodes are located at the apex of the axilla and receive lymph from all other axillary nodes; they would not typically be the first group to be affected. Central nodes receive lymph from other axillary nodes and are situated deeper within the axilla; they would also not be the primary nodes affected. Subscapular nodes, also known as posterior nodes, primarily drain the posterior thoracic wall.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 318.","responses":[{"text":"Central","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Subscapular","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Humeral","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pectoral","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Apical","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12843,"text":"A young man visits the neurology clinic with the complaint of being unable to flex both his arm and forearm. The lesion in this case is most likely to have affected which of the following rami of spinal nerves?","explanation":"In a case where the young man is unable to flex both his arm and forearm, the lesion is most likely to have affected the **ventral rami of C5, C6, and C7**. These spinal nerve segments contribute to the nerves that innervate muscles involved in the flexion of the arm (such as the biceps brachii, and brachialis) and forearm (like the flexor carpi radialis and flexor digitorum superficialis).\r\n\r\nDorsal rami are generally responsible for innervating muscles that help in extension and are not primarily involved in the flexion of the arm or forearm. Ventral rami of C3 and C4 are mainly associated with the cervical plexus and do not contribute significantly to arm or forearm flexion. Ventral rami of C8 and T1 would contribute to the lower part of the brachial plexus affecting more of the hand and intrinsic muscles of the forearm, not necessarily the flexion of the arm and forearm.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 189, 193, 204.","responses":[{"text":"Dorsal rami of C6, C7 and C8","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventral rami of C3 and C4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventral rami of C8 and T1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventral rami of C5, C6 and C7","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Dorsal rami of T1","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12846,"text":"A 40-year-old male is brought to the emergency department after falling from a ladder. X-ray and further examination reveal the flattening of the lateral longitudinal arch of the foot. Which of the following bone is most likely to be displaced in this case?","explanation":"The bone most likely to be displaced in the case of **flattening of the lateral longitudinal arch** of the foot is the **cuboid**. This bone is a key structural element in the lateral longitudinal arch and its displacement or fracture could contribute to a flattening of the arch.\r\n\r\nThe cuneiform and navicular bones are more involved in the medial longitudinal arch of the foot. The talus is a tarsal bone that serves as a fulcrum for the medial longitudinal arch but is not typically involved in the lateral arch. The medial three metatarsals are also primarily associated with the medial arch rather than the lateral one. Displacement or injury of these would be more likely to affect the medial arch.","reference":"1.Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 814.\r\n  \r\n2.Szczepanowska-Wołowiec B, Sztandera P, Kotela I, Zak M. Assessment of \r\nthe foot’s longitudinal arch by different indicators and their correlation with the foot loading paradigm in school-aged children: a cross sectional study. International Journal of Environmental Research and Public Health. Published May 13, 2021. Accessed December 4, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8153339/","responses":[{"text":"Cuneiform","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Navicular","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Talus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medial three metatarsals","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cuboid","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12847,"text":"During a tutorial class, students were discussing the development of bone. The development of bones without a pre-existing cartilage framework is termed?","explanation":"The development of bones **without a pre-existing cartilage framework** is termed **intramembranous ossification**. In contrast, endochondral ossification involves the formation of bone from a pre-existing cartilage model. Lamellar and non-lamellar are terms used to describe the microscopic structure of bone tissue, not the process of its development. Intracartilaginous is not a term used to describe a method of bone development.","reference":"Mescher AL, Junqueira LCU. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill; 2021: 149.","responses":[{"text":"Endochondral","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Non-lamellar","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intracartilaginous","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lamellar","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intramembranous","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12848,"text":"During a histology class, students were given a slide of fibrocartilage to identify. Fibrocartilage is characterized by which of the following features at the light microscope level?","explanation":"Fibrocartilage is characterized by an **acidophilic matrix**, which appears pinkish when stained and viewed under a light microscope due to the **presence of type I collagen fibers** and **fewer proteoglycans**.\r\n\r\nFibrocartilage typically lacks a distinct perichondrium and has a hyaline (not mineralized) matrix. The presence of collagen fibers (both type I \u0026 II) is not characteristic of fibrocartilage\r\n\r\nElastic fibers are not a prominent feature of fibrocartilage .","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 134.","responses":[{"text":"Mineralized matrix","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Collagen fibers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Elastic fibers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acidophilic","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Perichondrium","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12856,"text":"During class, the structure and growth of long bones were discussed. The growth of long bones is a result of which of the following?","explanation":"The growth of long bones is a result of **endochondral deposition of bone**. In this process, a cartilage model is first formed and later replaced by bone tissue. \r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nInterstitial growth of cartilage tissue contributes to the lengthening of the cartilage model, but the actual bone formation is endochondral. Interstitial growth of bone tissue is not how long bones grow. Appositional deposition of bone tissue contributes to the widening of bones but not their lengthening. Removal of calcified cartilage is a part of the endochondral bone formation process but not the sole method of long bone growth.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 151.","responses":[{"text":"Endochondral deposition of bone","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Removal of calcified cartilage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Appositional deposition of bone tissue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Interstitial growth of bone tissue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Interstitial growth of cartilage tissue","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12858,"text":"Osteoclasts originate from which of the following cells?","explanation":"**Osteoclasts** originate from **monocytes**. Monocytes are a type of white blood cell that can differentiate into macrophages and then fuse to form multinucleated osteoclasts, which are responsible for **bone resorption**.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nOsteoblasts are cells that are responsible for bone formation and do not give rise to osteoclasts. Osteocytes are mature bone cells that originate from osteoblasts and are involved in the maintenance of bone tissue. Osteoprogenitor cells are stem cells that differentiate into osteoblasts, not osteoclasts. Chondrocytes are cells that produce cartilage and are not precursors to osteoclasts.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 143.","responses":[{"text":"Osteocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Osteoblasts","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Osteoprogenitor cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Monocytes","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Chondrocytes","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12859,"text":"Which of the following is a feature of hyaline cartilage?","explanation":"**Hyaline cartilage** is located at the **articular ends of bones**. This type of cartilage provides a smooth surface for articulation, reducing friction and absorbing shock at the joints.\r\n\r\nChondrocytes arranged as parallel rows are more characteristic of fibrocartilage. Hyaline cartilage primarily contains type 2 collagen, not type 1. It can undergo both appositional and interstitial growth, rather than interstitial growth only. Hyaline cartilage is also avascular, meaning it does not contain vascular tissue.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 129.","responses":[{"text":"Vascular tissue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Located at articular ends of bone","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"It undergoes interstitial growth only","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Contains type 1 collagen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chondrocytes arranged as parallel rows","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12888,"text":"The physical properties of cartilage depend upon which of the following components of the matrix?","explanation":"The physical properties of cartilage depend upon **collagen type 2 fibrils**. Collagen provides **tensile strength** to the cartilage matrix, allowing it to withstand various mechanical forces. \r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nHydroxyapatite crystals are primarily found in bone and are responsible for its rigidity. Chondronectin is a cell adhesion molecule but does not primarily dictate the physical properties. Neurovascular bundles are not present in cartilage, as it is avascular. Fibronectin is a glycoprotein that helps in cell adhesion, migration, and other processes but is not the primary determinant of the physical properties of cartilage.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 129.","responses":[{"text":"Neurovascular bundles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Collagen type 2 fibrils","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibronectin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chondronectin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hydroxyapatite crystals","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12890,"text":"Which of the following is the incorrect statement regarding the development of skeletal muscle of the limbs?","explanation":"**Limb muscles** actually belong to the **abaxial domain**, not the primaxial domain. The primaxial domain includes muscles of the back and intercostal muscles, whereas the abaxial domain includes muscles of the limbs and body wall.\r\n\r\nDuring limb muscle development, the patterning of muscles is influenced by the connective tissue derived from the lateral plate mesoderm (specifically the parietal layer). This connective tissue plays a crucial role in guiding the formation and organization of limb muscles.\r\n\r\nLimb muscles are primarily innervated by ventral primary rami of spinal nerves.\r\n\r\nThe paraxial mesoderm gives rise to skeletal muscles, more specifically the ventrolateral edge of somites.","reference":"Sadler TW. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 14th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 170, 171.","responses":[{"text":"Patterning of limb muscles is controlled by connective tissue derived from parietal layer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Innervated by ventral primary rami","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Paraxial mesoderm will form muscles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Develop from ventrolateral edge of somites","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They belong to primaxial domain","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12899,"text":"During a hair transplant procedure, the patient receives local anesthesia on his scalp, after which he does not feel any pain from subsequent injections or punctures. Action potential did not develop in the nerve fibers responsible for carrying the sensation of pain due to which of the following reasons?","explanation":"The most likely reason the patient does not feel pain is due to the **blockage of voltage-gated sodium channels**. Local anesthetics commonly work by blocking these channels, which inhibits the initiation and propagation of action potentials in the pain-sensitive nerve fibers. This prevents the sensation of pain from being transmitted to the brain.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nBlockage of ligand-gated potassium channels is not how local anesthetics typically work. Potassium channels play a role in repolarization but are not the main target of local anesthetics.\r\n\r\nVoltage-gated potassium channels are involved in the repolarization phase of the action potential, but local anesthetics primarily target sodium channels to inhibit the action potential initiation.\r\n\r\nOpening of ligand-gated sodium channels would likely enhance, not inhibit, the ability to generate an action potential, thus this choice is incorrect.\r\n\r\nEarly closure of voltage-gated potassium channels is not the mechanism by which local anesthetics work. Such an event would rather prolong the action potential.","reference":"Garmon EH, Huecker MR. Topical, local, and regional anesthesia and anesthetics. StatPearls. Published 2022. Accessed December 5, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430894/","responses":[{"text":"Opening of ligand gated sodium channels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blockage of voltage gated sodium channels","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Blockage of ligand gated potassium channels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Early closure of voltage gated potassium channels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blockage of voltage gated potassium channels","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12905,"text":"What is the role of Schwann cells in neurotransmission?","explanation":"Schwann cells enhance the **speed of action potentials** along the axon. They produce myelin, a lipid-rich substance that wraps around the axon in a spiral pattern. This myelination allows for **saltatory conduction**, where the action potential \"jumps\" from one node of Ranvier to the next, effectively speeding up the rate at which the action potential travels down the axon.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nWhile myelin does provide some insulating qualities, its main purpose is to speed up neural transmission.\r\n\r\nSchwann cells actually increase (not limit) the speed of the action potential through myelination.\r\n\r\nThe speed of neurotransmission at the synapse depends on various other factors like the type of neurotransmitter and receptors involved, and not on myelination by Schwann cells.\r\n\r\nProtecting the neuronal soma from trauma is not a function of Schwann cells.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 74.","responses":[{"text":"Fast transmission at synapse","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thermal insulation of neuronal axons","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Enhance speed of action potential","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Protect the neuronal soma from trauma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Limit the speed of action potential","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12907,"text":"A 28-year-old visits the clinic complaining of an initial weakness of facial and neck muscles leading to double vision and difficulty in swallowing. Later on, the muscles of the upper and lower limbs are also involved. She mentions that the weakness becomes worse in the evening. This condition is a result of antibodies being produced against which of the following?","explanation":"**Myasthenia gravis (MG)** is characterized by weakness of facial and neck muscles followed by weakness in the limbs, which worsens in the evening.\r\n\r\nIn MG, antibodies are produced against **acetylcholine receptors** at the **motor end plate** of neuromuscular junctions. These antibodies interfere with the normal binding of acetylcholine to its receptors, leading to muscle weakness and fatigue.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nWhile acetylcholine plays a crucial role in neuromuscular transmission, in myasthenia gravis (MG), it's the antibodies targeting the acetylcholine receptors that lead to muscle weakness, not acetylcholine itself.\r\n\r\nAcetylcholinesterase is an enzyme responsible for breaking down acetylcholine at the neuromuscular junction. MG does not involve antibodies against acetylcholinesterase.\r\n\r\nMG primarily affects the postsynaptic membrane at the neuromuscular junction, where acetylcholine receptors are located, rather than the presynaptic membrane.\r\n\r\nThe motor endplate is the location where antibodies target acetylcholine receptors in MG, leading to muscle weakness and fatigue.","reference":"(1) Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 97.\r\n(2) Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 198, 199.","responses":[{"text":"Motor end plate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acetylcholine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acetylcholine receptors","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Presynaptic membrane","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acetylcholinesterase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12908,"text":"Muscle contraction is made possible when myosin heads attach to and walk along the thin filaments at both ends of a sarcomere, progressively pulling the thin filaments towards which of the following structures?","explanation":"Muscle contraction involves the interaction between **myosin** and **actin filaments** within the sarcomeres. The myosin heads attach to actin filaments and \"walk\" along them, causing the thin filaments to slide toward the center of the sarcomere. The **M line** is a structural feature located at the center of the sarcomere, and it serves as an anchor for the myosin filaments. As the myosin heads pull the actin filaments, they move toward the M line, which results in muscle contraction.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nThe Z disc is the structure at the end of a sarcomere that serves as an anchor point for the thin filaments and marks the boundary between adjacent sarcomeres.\r\n\r\nThe I band contains only thin filaments and gets narrower as the sarcomere contracts.\r\n\r\nThe A band contains both thick and thin filaments and does not change in length during contraction.\r\n\r\nThe H zone is the central region of the A band where only thick filaments are present, and it shortens during contraction.","reference":"Cooper GM. Actin, myosin, and cell movement. The Cell: A Molecular Approach. 2nd edition. Published 2000. Accessed December 5, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK9961/","responses":[{"text":"M line","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"A band","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"I band","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Z disc","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"H zone","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12909,"text":"Inside the sarcoplasmic reticulum of the skeletal muscle cells, calcium binds with which of the following protein?","explanation":"Inside the sarcoplasmic reticulum of skeletal muscle cells, calcium binds with the protein **calsequestrin**, which serves as a **calcium-binding protein** within the sarcoplasmic reticulum, helping to store and regulate calcium ions, crucial for muscle contraction.\r\n\r\nCalmodulin is another calcium-binding protein, but it primarily functions in the cytoplasm, playing a role in various cellular processes, including signal transduction, rather than calcium storage in the sarcoplasmic reticulum.\r\n\r\nCalexcitin and calbindin are not typically associated with calcium storage or regulation in muscle cells.\r\n\r\nCalcineurin is a calcium-dependent enzyme involved in signaling pathways like the immune response and neuronal signaling but is not primarily responsible for calcium storage in the sarcoplasmic reticulum of muscle cells.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 98.","responses":[{"text":"Calexcitin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calbindin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calseqeustrin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Calmodulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcineurin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12910,"text":"The ATP present inside muscle fibers can only power contraction for a few seconds before it runs out. Which of the following is the next immediate source of energy?","explanation":"During intense muscle activity, such as a burst of high-intensity exercise or a sudden muscle contraction, the initial source of energy is **ATP (adenosine triphosphate)**. However, the ATP stored within muscle fibers is limited and can only support muscle contraction for a few seconds.\r\n\r\nWhen ATP is rapidly used up, the next immediate source of energy is **creatine phosphate**. Creatine phosphate, also known as phosphocreatine, is a high-energy phosphate compound stored within muscle cells. It serves as a rapid reservoir of energy and can quickly donate its phosphate group to ADP (adenosine diphosphate) to regenerate ATP. This process is catalyzed by the enzyme creatine kinase.\r\n\r\n---\r\nAerobic respiration is a slower but more sustainable energy production process that relies on oxygen and occurs in mitochondria. It becomes the primary source of energy during prolonged exercise.\r\n\r\nKrebs's citric acid cycle (also known as the citric acid cycle or TCA cycle) is part of aerobic respiration and occurs in the mitochondria to generate ATP.\r\n\r\nAnaerobic glycolysis is another pathway that can provide energy during intense exercise, but it generates ATP without the need for oxygen. It produces lactic acid as a byproduct and can support energy production for a short duration.\r\n\r\nMyoglobin is a protein found in muscle tissue that binds to and stores oxygen, helping to supply oxygen to muscle fibers during periods of increased demand. It is not a direct source of energy production but plays a role in oxygen transport within muscles.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 86.","responses":[{"text":"Kerb's citric acid cycle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aerobic respiration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Creatine phosphate","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Myoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anaerobic glycolysis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12911,"text":"Calcium is released by which of the following structures in the excitation-contraction coupling mechanism of skeletal muscle?","explanation":"In the **excitation-contraction coupling mechanism** of skeletal muscle, calcium ions (Ca2+) are released from the sarcoplasmic reticulum (SR) into the cytoplasm of muscle fibers. This release of calcium is triggered by the depolarization of the muscle cell membrane (sarcolemma) and is mediated by a specialized structure known as the **ryanodine receptor channels**. These channels are located on the membrane of the SR and are activated when an action potential travels along the sarcolemma.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nThe dihydropyridine receptors (DHPR) are voltage-sensitive L-type calcium channels located in the sarcolemma, and they play a role in the initial depolarization of the muscle cell.\r\n\r\nSERCA (sarcoplasmic Reticulum Ca2+-ATPase) is responsible for actively pumping calcium ions back into the SR during muscle relaxation.\r\n\r\nCalmodulin is a calcium-binding protein involved in various cellular processes but is not directly responsible for calcium release in excitation-contraction coupling.\r\n\r\nCalsequestrin is a protein found in the SR that binds to calcium ions and helps store them within the SR, but it does not release calcium.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 97.","responses":[{"text":"Calmodulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calsequestrin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ryanodine receptor channels","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Dihydropyridine receptors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"SERCA (sarcoplasmic reticulum Ca+2 -ATPase)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12912,"text":"Which of the following is a glycosylated protein that provides hydration along with swelling pressure to the tissue enabling it to withstand compressional forces?","explanation":"**Proteoglycans** are **glycosylated proteins** found in the extracellular matrix of connective tissues, including cartilage and the intervertebral disc. They play a crucial role in providing hydration and swelling pressure to the tissue, allowing it to withstand compressional forces. Proteoglycans consist of a core protein to which long chains of carbohydrates (glycosaminoglycans or GAGs) are attached. These carbohydrates attract water molecules, contributing to tissue hydration and resilience. While collagen provides structural strength, proteoglycans are essential for the tissue's ability to absorb and distribute compressive forces.","reference":"Yanagishita M. Function of proteoglycans in the extracellular matrix. Pathology International. Published June 1993. Accessed December 5, 2022. https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1440-1827.1993.tb02569.x","responses":[{"text":"Mucins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Proteoglycans","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Collagen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Laminin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12927,"text":"A 30-year-old male visits the outpatient department with a history of pain in the right hip joint region. An anteroposterior radiograph evaluation of the hip joint is carried out and is concluded to be normal based on the smooth line forming a continuous curve along the inferior margin of the femoral neck to the upper margin of the obturator foramen. What is the name of this line?","explanation":"**\"Shenton's line\"** forms a continuous curve along the inferior margin of the femoral neck to the upper margin of the obturator foramen on an anteroposterior radiograph of the hip joint.  This line is used as a diagnostic tool to assess the **integrity of the hip joint** and can help in identifying conditions such as hip dislocations or fractures.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nThe sacral arcuate line is a bony ridge on the posterior side of the pelvis, particularly associated with the sacrum.\r\n\r\nThe ilio-ischial line is also related to the pelvis and is used to assess certain pelvic fractures.\r\n\r\nThe ilio-pectineal line is used to evaluate certain conditions in the pelvis but does not specifically address the assessment of the hip joint on radiographs.\r\n\r\nThe line of Klein is a reference line used in dental radiography and is unrelated to the hip joint or its assessment.","reference":"1.Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 787.\r\n  \r\n2.Dow Lecture Slides. Locomotor Module. Subject: Radiology, Topic: Normal X-ray of the upper and lower limb, Subtopic: X-ray hip joint AP and lateral view.","responses":[{"text":"Ilio-pectineal line","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Line of Klein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Shenton's line","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ilio-ischial line","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sacral arcuate line","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12928,"text":"A 5-year-old boy sustains a fracture of the proximal tibia. X-ray reveals that the fracture line passes from the growth plate into the metaphysis. Which type of fracture is this according to Salter's classification of fractures?","explanation":"The fracture, where the fracture line passes from the growth plate into the metaphysis of the proximal tibia, corresponds to **type 2** in the Salter-Harris classification of fractures.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nType 4 fractures involve a fracture line that extends through the growth plate, the metaphysis, and the epiphysis.\r\n\r\nType 5 fractures are characterized by a crush injury to the growth plate. \r\n\r\nType 1 fractures involve a transverse fracture that passes through the growth plate but does not extend into the metaphysis or epiphysis.\r\n\r\nType 3 fractures occur when the fracture line passes from the epiphysis through the growth plate and into the metaphysis.","reference":"Levine RH, Foris LA, Nezwek TA, Waseem M. Salter harris fractures. StatPearls. Published 2022. Accessed December 5, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430688/","responses":[{"text":"Type 2","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Type 5","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type 4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type 1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type 3","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12932,"text":"A sudden explosion happens in a busy marketplace, after which rescue workers start assessing the injured and tagging them with different color codes. Which of the following term best describes this action?","explanation":"The action of assessing the injured and tagging them with different color codes in the aftermath of a disaster is known as **triage.** Triage is a crucial process that helps prioritize medical care for those affected based on the severity of their injuries, ensuring that those who require immediate attention receive it first.","reference":"(1) Triage and emergency assessment. Published 2008. Accessed December 5, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK143755/\r\n(2) Dow lecture slides. Locomotor Module, Subject: Community Medicine, Topic: Disaster Management, Sub-topic: Triage.","responses":[{"text":"Triage","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Field care","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Search","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rescue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Identification","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12933,"text":"The four principal components in managing humanitarian supplies are acquisition, transportation, storage, and distribution. These happen during which phase of disaster management?","explanation":"The four principal components in managing humanitarian supplies—**acquisition, transportation, storage, and distribution**—typically occur during the **relief phase of disaster management**. This is the phase when immediate needs for medical care, food, and shelter are met. \r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nThe search and rescue phase is more focused on locating and helping victims of the disaster, and field care deals with immediate medical treatment. The Impact phase is when the disaster actually occurs. Mitigation is concerned with measures that can prevent or lessen the impact of a future disaster.","reference":"Dow lecture slides. Locomotor module. Subject: Community medicine, Topic: Disaster management, Sub-topic: Relief phase","responses":[{"text":"Mitigation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Search and rescue phase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Relief phase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Field care","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Impact","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12935,"text":"Which of the following strategies of health promotion involves giving people the information and skills that they need to make healthy choices?","explanation":null,"reference":"Dow lecture slides. Locomotor module. Subject: Community Medicine, Topic: Health promotion and health education, Sub-topic: Strategies for health promotion.","responses":[{"text":"Mediating","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Advocacy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Health education","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Creating supportive environment","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Enabling","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12937,"text":"Which of the following is the best strategy to improve the access to promotive, preventive, and curative health care among the elderly?","explanation":null,"reference":"1. Araujo de Carvalho I, Epping-Jordan J, Pot AM, et al. Organizing integrated health-care services to meet older people’s needs. Bulletin of the World Health Organization. Published November 1, 2017. Accessed September 10, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5677611/\r\n\r\n2.Dow lecture slides. Locomotor module. Subject: Community medicine, Topic: Health of the elderly, Sub-topic: National program of health care for the elderly.","responses":[{"text":"Home based health services","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Special health care","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Community based health center","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hospital based services","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Medical camps","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12939,"text":"Which of the following principle addresses the allocation of healthcare resources in different social and geographical locations for the health of the population. It also means not only ensuring access to care for all but also fighting for social, economic, and environmental justice?","explanation":null,"reference":"Dow lecture slides. Locomotor module. Subject: Behavioural Sciences, Topic: Principles of medical ethics, Sub-topic: Justice- Fairness and equality.","responses":[{"text":"Conflict of interest","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Justice and equity","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Confidentiality","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Breaking bad news","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Informed consent","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12940,"text":"Healthcare decisions are based not only on clinical and technical grounds but also\r\non ethical grounds. Although clinicians consider the clinical and technical aspects,\r\nthere are situations when ethical aspects may be overlooked and healthcare\r\ndelivery that was planned or performed to help but brings unintended harm to the\r\npatient. Which of the following terms best describes this situation?","explanation":null,"reference":"Rodziewicz TL, Houseman B, Hipskind JE. Medical error reduction and prevention. StatPearls. Published 2022. Accessed December 5, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK499956/","responses":[{"text":"Justice","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medical error","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Beneficence","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Non-maleficence","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Autonomy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12944,"text":"A 32-year-old married lady visits the outpatient department with complaints of low mood, decreased interest, decreased energy, feeling guilty and low self-esteem. Upon inquiry, she had similar episodes a year ago and felt better after treatment by a psychiatrist. She discontinued treatment and didn't come to follow-up visits. Recently she is having strong suicidal ideation and intends to die. She has been advised admission to the psychiatry ward. However, the patient refuses to get admitted and urges to leave the hospital immediately. What would be the best option for management in this case?","explanation":null,"reference":"Le T, Vikas Bhushan. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2021. 31st ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2021: 273, 276.","responses":[{"text":"Seek consent from family for treatment","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"She can go home with advice to come back again after one week","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Start treatment without involving patient and family","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Her decision should be respected and she should be allowed to leave the hospital","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"She can leave the hospital after signing \"Leaving against medical advice\"","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12945,"text":"A 30-year-old divorced and unemployed male has been taking psychiatric medications for the last three years. He was admitted to a psychiatric unit after a violent act of stabbing his friend. He discontinued his medications about a month ago and is again brought to the clinic by his family members who complain of him talking to himself and hearing the voices of people who are not around him. He thinks that one of his cousins is trying to kill him. A mental state examination reveals that he has the intention of killing his cousin but requests the doctor to not disclose this information.  What will be the most appropriate management for this case?","explanation":null,"reference":"Le T, Vikas Bhushan. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2021. 31st ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2021: 273.","responses":[{"text":"Disclosure of intent to kill, in this case, is not unethical","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"The patient should be given another chance to review his intent to kill","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Respect patients who wish to not disclose the information","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Autonomy to be treated is the right of the patient in this case","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Confidentiality in this case is the right of the patient","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12946,"text":"A mother brings her malnourished 4-year-old child to a medical officer in a rural hospital in a poverty-stricken area. The child has bowing of his legs and knobby protrusions on his ribcage. Bossing of the skull is also observed. Which of the following is the most appropriate statement regarding this patient?","explanation":null,"reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 192.","responses":[{"text":"Knobby protrusions are due to multiple fractures","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The child most likely has rickets","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"When this disease occurs in adults it is called osteoporosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Histologically this condition shows decreased amounts of normal bone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin D levels are normal","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12947,"text":"A 39-year-old lady presents to an orthopedic clinic with complaints of bone pain and difficulty in walking. Radiological examination reveals no pathology, except for the femur neck bone mass of 3.2 standard deviations from the normal population. The bone mineralization was found to be normal. What is the most appropriate diagnosis for this patient?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1187.","responses":[{"text":"Osteoporosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Osteomalacia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Osteogenesis imperfecta","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Osteodystrophy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Osteopenia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12948,"text":"A 10-year-old boy is brought to the clinic. His mother reports that he fell while playing cricket in the street 2 weeks ago and injured his knee, evident from the large wound just below the knee. The child complains of throbbing pain in the wound area. On examination, he has a fever. On wound inspection, there is yellowish pus oozing out of the wound with tiny fragments of bone in it. Which of the following statements is true regarding this patient?","explanation":null,"reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 193.","responses":[{"text":"A complete blood picture will show leucopenia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The most likely diagnosis is osteomyelitis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"He has Pott's disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Wound culture will show gram-negative rods","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dead bone fragments are called involucrum","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12951,"text":"A 13-year-old male had an enlarging mass in the left thigh for two months. It was not associated with pain or tenderness. The X-ray revealed a large tumor extending around the entire shaft and lower third of the left femur. An amputation was performed after the biopsy. This tumor comprises atypical osteoblastic cells that have large\r\nhyperchromatic nuclei with nuclear pleomorphism and frequent mitoses. Which of\r\nthe following enzymes is expected to be raised in this case?","explanation":null,"reference":"Saraç F, Saygılı F. Causes of high bone alkaline phosphatase. Biotechnology \u0026 Biotechnological Equipment. Published January 2007. Accessed December 5, 2022. http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/13102818.2007.10817444","responses":[{"text":"Alkaline phosphatase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pyruvate oxygenase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superoxide dismutase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Heme oxygenase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acid phophatase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12953,"text":"Which of the following factors stimulate the release of parathyroid hormone?","explanation":"Parathyroid hormone (PTH) is released by the parathyroid glands primarily in response to **low levels of calcium in the blood**. One of its main actions is to raise calcium levels by increasing bone resorption, enhancing calcium reabsorption in the kidneys, and increasing the production of calcitriol (active Vitamin D), which increases calcium absorption from the gut. **High levels of phosphate** also stimulate the release of PTH, as it works to decrease phosphate levels by promoting renal excretion.\r\n\r\n**High phosphate and low vitamin D levels in blood**: Although high phosphate stimulates PTH release, low vitamin D levels would generally reduce calcium levels, not stimulate PTH release directly.\r\n\r\n**High calcium and low vitamin D levels in blood**: High calcium would actually inhibit PTH release.\r\n\r\n**Low calcium and high vitamin D levels in blood**: High vitamin D would typically lead to increased calcium absorption, which would not stimulate PTH release.\r\n\r\n**High phosphate and high calcium levels in blood**: High calcium would inhibit PTH release, despite the stimulating effect of high phosphate.","reference":"(1) de Francisco ALM, Cobo MA, Setien MA, et al. Effect of serum phosphate on parathyroid hormone secretion during hemodialysis. Kidney International. Published 1998. Accessed December 5, 2022. https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0085253815308528\r\n\r\n(2) Khan M, Jose A, Sharma S. Physiology, parathyroid hormone. StatPearls. Published 2022. Accessed December 5, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK499940/","responses":[{"text":"Low calcium and high vitamin D levels in blood","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"High calcium and low vitamin D levels in blood","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"High phosphate and high calcium levels in blood","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"High phosphate and low calcium levels in blood","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"High phosphate and low vitamin D levels in blood","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12957,"text":"A 25-year-old female presents to an orthopedic clinic with a history of a fall on an outstretched hand 2 days ago. She sustained a fracture in her right radius at its distal end. Which of the following is the appropriate stage of healing fracture in this case?","explanation":"The **Inflammatory Phase** is the initial stage of fracture healing that typically occurs immediately after the injury and lasts for several days. In this phase, a hematoma forms at the fracture site, and inflammatory cells such as neutrophils and macrophages migrate to the area. This sets the stage for subsequent healing processes.\r\n\r\n**Consolidation Phase**: This is the second phase of bone healing, following the inflammatory phase, characterized by the deposition of new bone.\r\n\r\n**Remodeling Phase**: This is the final stage of bone healing where the newly formed bone is remodeled to restore its original shape and mechanical properties.\r\n\r\n**Resorption Phase**: Resorption is a part of the remodeling phase where excess bone is removed. It is not a distinct phase of fracture healing.\r\n\r\n**Reparative Phase**: Also known as the fibrocartilaginous callus formation, this phase comes after the inflammatory phase and involves the formation of a soft callus around the fracture site.","reference":"Sheen JR, Garla VV. Fracture healing overview. StatPearls. Published 2022. Accessed December 5, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK551678/","responses":[{"text":"Resorption phase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reparative phase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inflammatory phase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Consolidation phase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Remodeling phase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12961,"text":"What is the most important primary prevention method to control automobile accidents and resulting injuries?","explanation":"The **Enforcement of Traffic Rules** is the most critical primary prevention method for controlling automobile accidents and the resulting injuries. When traffic rules are strictly enforced, it creates a safer environment by regulating speed, right-of-way, and other crucial driving behaviors, thereby significantly reducing the risk of accidents.\r\n\r\n\r\n**Speed Control**: While controlling speed is essential, it is a part of the broader category of enforcing traffic rules. Speed limits by themselves won't prevent accidents due to other factors like reckless driving, not yielding right-of-way, etc.\r\n\r\n**Properly Constructed Roads**: Although essential, even the best-constructed roads won't prevent accidents if traffic rules are not followed.\r\n\r\n**Avoid Overloading of Public**: Overloading is a risk factor for accidents but again falls under the broader category of enforcing traffic rules, which would include regulations against overloading.\r\n\r\n**Vehicles Checked for Mechanical Faults**: This is also important but won't prevent accidents due to human error, which is a significant cause of road accidents.","reference":"1.Park K. Park’s Textbook of Preventive and Social Medicine. 25th ed. Bhanot Publishers; 2019: 440.\r\n\r\n2.Dow lecture slides. Locomotor module. Subject: Community medicine, Topic: Injury, Sub-topic: Prevention.","responses":[{"text":"Speed control","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Avoid overloading of public","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Enforcement of traffic rules","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Vehicles checked for mechanical faults","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Properly constructed roads","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12965,"text":"Which of the following potential is produced when there is a spontaneous release of acetylcholine at the neuromuscular junction?","explanation":"A **Miniature End-Plate Potential (MEPP)** is a small, localized change in membrane potential that occurs spontaneously due to the release of a quantum of acetylcholine (ACh) at the neuromuscular junction. MEPPs are sub-threshold, meaning they are not large enough to initiate an action potential but are important for understanding the basic physiology of neurotransmission.\r\n\r\n**Resting Membrane Potential**: This is the steady-state electrical charge of a neuron or muscle cell when it is not active. It is not generated by the release of ACh.\r\n\r\n**Post-Tetanic Potential**: This occurs following repetitive stimulation (tetanic stimulation) and indicates a heightened sensitivity to additional stimuli. It is not caused by the spontaneous release of ACh.\r\n\r\n**Action Potential**: This is a self-propagating wave of depolarization that travels along the membrane, usually initiated by reaching the threshold potential. It is not directly caused by the spontaneous release of ACh.\r\n\r\n**Threshold Potential**: This is the membrane potential at which an action potential is initiated. The release of ACh can help a cell reach its threshold potential, but the spontaneous release of ACh generates MEPPs, which are usually sub-threshold.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 95.","responses":[{"text":"Action potential","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Resting membrane potential","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Post-tetanic potential","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Miniature end-plate potential","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Threshold potential","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13326,"text":"A patient suffering from osteoporosis was told to get a blood test done for the assessment of bone turnover. Which of the following is the most appropriate test for this?","explanation":"**Tartrate-Resistant Acid Phosphatase (TRAP)** is an enzyme that is highly expressed in osteoclasts, the cells responsible for bone resorption. The level of TRAP in the blood serves as an excellent marker for osteoclast activity and, consequently, bone turnover. This is particularly pertinent for patients with osteoporosis, who may have an imbalance between bone formation and bone resorption.\r\n\r\n**C-telopeptide and N-telopeptide**: These are breakdown products of Type I collagen and can also indicate bone resorption. However, they are not as specific as TRAP for assessing bone turnover in osteoporosis.\r\n\r\n**Alkaline Phosphatase**: This enzyme is a marker for bone formation rather than resorption and is not as specific for assessing osteoporosis, as it can also be elevated in liver disease.\r\n\r\n**Deoxypyridinoline**: This is another marker for bone resorption but is generally considered less sensitive and specific than TRAP for assessing osteoporosis.","reference":"1. Kikuchi W, Ichihara K, Mori K, Shimizu Y. Biological sources of variations of tartrate-resistant acid phosphatase 5b in a healthy Japanese population. Annals of Clinical Biochemistry. Published July 2021. Accessed September 8, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8258717/\r\n\r\n\r\n2.Dow lecture slides. Locomotor module. Subject: Biochemistry, Topic: Bone Markers, Sub-topic: Bone resorption markers in blood.","responses":[{"text":"Deoxypyridinoline","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"N-telopeptide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alkaline phosphatase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tartrate-resistant acid phosphatase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"C-telopeptide","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16030,"text":"Which of the following can be seen in the H-zone of skeletal muscles?","explanation":"The **H-zone** of skeletal muscles is primarily composed of **myosin filaments**. The H-zone is a region within the A-band of a sarcomere where only myosin filaments are present, and actin filaments do not overlap. \r\n---\r\n\r\n**A-band**: The region of a sarcomere that contains the entire length of a single myosin filament and overlapping portions of actin filaments. The H-zone is a part of the A-band.\r\n\r\n**Z-band**: This marks the boundary of individual sarcomeres and is not found within the H-zone. The Z-band contains proteins like alpha-actinin that anchor the thin actin filaments.\r\n\r\n**Actin**: Actin is the primary component of thin filaments and does not exist in the H-zone, which is specifically a part of the A-band where only myosin filaments are present without any overlapping actin.\r\n\r\n**Nebulin**: This is a protein that helps to regulate the length of actin filaments and is not present in the H-zone where only myosin filaments are found.","reference":"(1) Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 98.\r\n  \r\n\r\n(2) Pham S, Puckett Y. Physiology, skeletal muscle contraction. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2023. Accessed July 10, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK559006/","responses":[{"text":"Nebulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Actin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A-band","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Myosin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Z-band","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16031,"text":"Which muscles are part of the anterior axio-appendicular upper limb musculature?","explanation":"The **Serratus Anterior** is part of the anterior axio-appendicular muscles that connect the axial skeleton to the appendicular skeleton of the upper limb. It originates from the surface of the upper eight or nine ribs and inserts onto the anterior surface of the medial border of the scapula. Its primary function is to protract and stabilize the scapula, facilitating the upward rotation required for overhead arm movements.\r\n\r\n**Rhomboid Major**: This muscle is part of the posterior axio-appendicular musculature. It attaches the scapula to the spinal column and is responsible for retracting the scapula.\r\n\r\n**Levator Scapulae**: Similar to the Rhomboid Major, the Levator Scapulae is also a part of the posterior axio-appendicular musculature and is involved in elevating and retracting the scapula.\r\n\r\n**Lateral Dorsi**: There is no \"Lateral Dorsi\" muscle. You may be referring to the Latissimus Dorsi, which is a part of the posterior axio-appendicular musculature and primarily serves in adducting, extending, and internally rotating the arm.\r\n\r\n**Trapezius**: Although the Trapezius muscle affects the positioning of the scapula and the upper limb, it is a part of the posterior axio-appendicular musculature.","reference":"1.Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 168.\r\n  \r\n\r\n2.Javed O, Maldonado KA, Ashmyan R. Anatomy, shoulder and upper limb, muscles. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2023. Accessed June 11, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482410/","responses":[{"text":"Lateral dorsi","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serratus anterior","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Rhomboid major","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Levator scapulae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Trapezius","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16032,"text":"What is the absence of a proximal aspect of a limb with rudimentary of hand or foot only is called?","explanation":"**Phocomelia** refers to a congenital condition characterized by the absence of the proximal segments of the limbs, leaving only rudimentary hands or feet attached directly to the trunk. This condition can give the limbs a flipper-like appearance and is most commonly associated with thalidomide exposure during pregnancy.\r\n\r\n**Micromelia**: This term refers to limbs that are formed but shorter than normal. In micromelia, the entire limb is typically present but reduced in size, which distinguishes it from phocomelia.\r\n\r\n**Dysmelia**: This is a general term that refers to congenital limb malformations. It doesn't specifically describe the absence of the proximal limb segments while leaving rudimentary hands or feet, as phocomelia does.\r\n\r\n**Meromelia**: This refers to the absence of a part of a limb. Some portion of the limb is usually present, which is unlike phocomelia where only rudimentary hands or feet are present attached to the trunk.\r\n\r\n**Amelia**: Amelia refers to the complete absence of a limb, making it distinct from phocomelia where some part (usually rudimentary hands or feet) is present.","reference":"Davis, Donald D., and Steven M. Kane. ‘Phocomelia’. StatPearls, 2023, http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK559212/","responses":[{"text":"Micromelia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dysmelia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amelia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Meromelia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phocomelia","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16033,"text":"Which of the following nerves is damaged due to a blow to the lateral side of the knee?","explanation":"The **Fibular Nerve** runs close to the surface at the lateral aspect of the knee, making it vulnerable to injury from a blow to this area. This nerve is a branch of the sciatic nerve and is responsible for dorsiflexion and eversion of the foot. Damage to this nerve can result in \"foot drop,\" characterized by an inability to dorsiflex the foot.\r\n\r\n**Sciatic Nerve**: While the fibular nerve is a branch of the sciatic nerve, the latter is not typically exposed to direct injury from a blow to the lateral side of the knee because it runs more posteriorly and deeply.\r\n\r\n**Tibial Nerve**: The tibial nerve is another branch of the sciatic nerve but runs on the posterior aspect of the leg. It is not susceptible to injury from a lateral blow to the knee.\r\n\r\n**Gluteal Nerve**: The gluteal nerves serve the gluteal muscles in the hip region and are not related to the knee. Therefore, they would not be damaged by a blow to the lateral knee.\r\n\r\n**Saphenous Nerve**: This nerve is a branch of the femoral nerve and runs along the medial aspect of the knee and leg. It would not be affected by a blow to the lateral side of the knee.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 776.","responses":[{"text":"Tibial nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibular nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sciatic nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gluteal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Saphenous nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16034,"text":"Which nerve is affected when one can't dorsiflex and evert their foot?","explanation":"The **Common Peroneal Nerve**, also known as the common fibular nerve, is responsible for both dorsiflexion and eversion of the foot. It is a branch of the sciatic nerve and gives rise to the superficial and deep fibular nerves which innervate the muscles responsible for these movements.\r\n\r\n- **Dorsiflexion** is primarily controlled by the tibialis anterior muscle, which is innervated by the deep fibular nerve.\r\n- **Eversion** is mainly mediated by the peroneus longus and peroneus brevis muscles, both innervated by the superficial fibular nerve.\r\n\r\n**Tibial Nerve**: This nerve is responsible for plantarflexion and inversion of the foot. Thus, if the tibial nerve were affected, it would not present as an inability to dorsiflex and evert the foot.\r\n\r\n**Obturator Nerve**: This nerve primarily serves the adductors of the thigh and does not have a role in foot dorsiflexion or eversion.\r\n\r\n**Gluteal Nerve**: The gluteal nerves innervate the gluteal muscles in the hip area and are not involved in dorsiflexion or eversion of the foot.\r\n\r\n**Sciatic Nerve**: Although the common peroneal nerve is a branch of the sciatic nerve, the sciatic nerve itself also gives rise to the tibial nerve. So if the sciatic nerve were affected, you'd expect a wider array of symptoms affecting both plantarflexion and dorsiflexion, making it less specific to the question stem.","reference":"1.Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 764.\r\n  \r\n\r\n\r\n2.Lezak, Bradley, et al. ‘Peroneal Nerve Injury’. StatPearls, 2023, http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK549859/","responses":[{"text":"Peroneal nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Gluteal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sciatic nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Obturator nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tibial nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16035,"text":"What is it called if a whole limb is not formed?","explanation":"**Amelia** refers to the congenital absence of one or more limbs. It is a condition in which a limb fails to form entirely during embryonic development. The absence of the whole limb differentiates Amelia from other limb malformation disorders.\r\n\r\n**Micromelia** is a condition where the limbs are formed but are shorter than usual. It does not involve the complete absence of the limb, so it is not the correct choice for this question.\r\n\r\n**Dysmelia** is a general term for congenital limb anomalies but does not necessarily mean the absence of the entire limb. \r\n\r\n**Phocomelia** involves the absence of the proximal segments of limbs, meaning the limbs are severely shortened and have flipper-like appearance. However, some limb structure is present, making this option incorrect for describing a complete absence of a limb.\r\n\r\n**Meromelia** is a condition in which a part of a limb is missing, but unlike Amelia, some portion of the limb is usually present.","reference":"Eghbalian, Fatemeh, et al. ‘Amelia: A Case Report and Literature Review’. Iranian Journal of Pediatrics, Dec. 2015, https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4662846/","responses":[{"text":"Phocomelia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Micromelia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amelia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Meromelia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dysmelia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16036,"text":"What is the pathology called if a child is born with no formation of the forearm?","explanation":"Meromelia is a congenital condition characterized by the partial absence of one or more limbs, such as the forearm. In cases of meromelia involving the forearm, the child is born with an incomplete or underdeveloped forearm, which can vary in severity.\r\n\r\n\r\n- **Phocomelia**: Phocomelia is a related condition characterized by severe limb abnormalities in which the hands or feet are attached directly to the body, resembling flippers.\r\n  \r\n- **Amelia**: Amelia refers to the complete absence of one or more limbs. In cases of forearm absence, it would be considered a form of amelia.\r\n  \r\n- **Dysmelia**: Dysmelia is a general term used to describe various congenital limb abnormalities, including meromelia.\r\n  \r\n- **Micromelia**: Micromelia refers to abnormally short limbs but does not necessarily involve the absence of specific limb segments like the forearm.","reference":"Davis DD, Kane SM. Meromelia. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed June 13, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK560765/","responses":[{"text":"Micromelia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amelia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Meromelia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Phocomelia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dysmelia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16037,"text":"The scapula overlies which of the following ribs?","explanation":"The scapula, commonly known as the shoulder blade, overlies the second through seventh ribs. It is situated on the posterior aspect of the thorax and contributes to the shoulder joint, providing attachment points for various muscles involved in shoulder movement and stability.\r\n\r\n#### Incorrect Options:\r\n\r\n- **First-ninth**: The scapula does not directly overlie the first rib.\r\n  \r\n- **Third-seventh**: While it does overlie the third rib, it also covers ribs below and above this level.\r\n  \r\n- **Second-fifth**: This option only includes the first four ribs and does not encompass the full range of ribs overlaid by the scapula.\r\n  \r\n- **Fourth-ninth**: This option includes ribs beyond the extent typically overlaid by the scapula.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 151.","responses":[{"text":"First-ninth","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Second-seventh","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Fourth-ninth","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Third-seventh","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Second-fifth","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16038,"text":"Which of the following is secreted by osteoblasts during bone remodeling?","explanation":"Bone alkaline phosphatase is an enzyme secreted by osteoblasts during bone remodeling. It plays a critical role in bone mineralization by facilitating the deposition of calcium and phosphate ions into the bone matrix. Measuring BALP levels is often used as a clinical marker for bone formation and can help assess the activity of osteoblasts.\r\n\r\n#### Incorrect Options:\r\n\r\n- **Osteocalcin**: Osteocalcin is a protein produced by osteoblasts and plays a role in bone mineralization, but it is not an enzyme.\r\n  \r\n- **Procollagen type 1**: This is a precursor molecule in collagen synthesis, not an enzyme secreted by osteoblasts.\r\n  \r\n- **Collagen type 1 propeptide**: Propeptides are components of collagen synthesis and are not secreted enzymes involved in bone mineralization.\r\n  \r\n- **Procollagen type 2**: Procollagen type 2 is involved in the formation of cartilage and is not secreted during bone remodeling.","reference":"1.Mescher AL, Junqueira LCU. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill; 2021: 141.\r\n  \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n2.Rucci N. Molecular biology of bone remodelling. Clinical Cases in Mineral and Bone Metabolism. Published 2008. Accessed June 13, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2781193/","responses":[{"text":"Procollagen type 2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Procollagen type 1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Osteocalcin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Collagen type 1 propeptide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"BALP","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16041,"text":"Which of the following ligaments prevents the backward dislocation of the medial end of the clavicle?","explanation":"The interclavicular ligament is a broad, fibrous band that connects the sternal ends of the clavicles at the top of the sternum (breastbone). It serves to prevent the backward or posterior dislocation of the medial ends of the clavicles. This ligament contributes to the stability of the sternoclavicular joint.\r\n\r\n#### Incorrect Options:\r\n\r\n- **Coracoclavicular ligament**: Connects the clavicle to the coracoid process of the scapula and is primarily involved in the stability of the acromioclavicular joint.\r\n  \r\n- **Acromioclavicular ligament**: Also involved in the stability of the acromioclavicular joint, not in preventing backward dislocation of the medial clavicle.\r\n  \r\n- **Coracoacromial ligament**: Stabilizes the space between the acromion process and the coracoid process of the scapula, not related to the sternoclavicular joint.\r\n  \r\n- **Costoclavicular ligament**: Connects the clavicle to the first rib and is not involved in preventing backward dislocation of the medial clavicle.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 694.","responses":[{"text":"Costoclavicular ligament","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Coracoacromial ligament","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Interclavicular ligament","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Acromioclavicular ligament","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Coracoclavicular ligament","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16042,"text":"Nerve injury to which of the following causes winging of the scapula?","explanation":"The **long thoracic nerve** innervates the **serratus anterior muscle**, which plays a crucial role in stabilizing the scapula against the rib cage. When the long thoracic nerve is injured or compromised, it can result in dysfunction of the serratus anterior muscle, leading to a winging of the scapula. This condition is known as \"scapular winging.\"\r\n\r\n\r\n- **Dorsal scapular nerve**: Innervates the rhomboid muscles but is not primarily responsible for scapular winging.\r\n  \r\n- **Accessory nerve**: Also known as the cranial nerve XI, it innervates the trapezius muscle but does not directly cause scapular winging when injured.\r\n  \r\n- **Axillary nerve**: Innervates the deltoid muscle but is not associated with scapular winging.\r\n  \r\n- **Suprascapular nerve**: Innervates the supraspinatus and infraspinatus muscles but does not cause scapular winging when injured.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 179.","responses":[{"text":"Accessory nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Suprascapular nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dorsal scapular nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Long thoracic nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Axillary nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16045,"text":"Which of the following muscles prevents the displacement of the clavicle in fractures?","explanation":"The Subclavius muscle originates from the first rib and its cartilage and inserts into the inferior surface of the clavicle. This muscle plays a role in stabilizing the clavicle, particularly preventing its upward displacement in cases of fractures. The muscle's function is important in maintaining the integrity of the clavicle in the event of trauma.\r\n\r\n#### Incorrect Options:\r\n\r\n- **Sternocleidomastoid**: This muscle acts on the head and neck, not directly on the clavicle.\r\n  \r\n- **Trapezius**: While it attaches to the clavicle, it is not primarily responsible for preventing its displacement in fractures.\r\n  \r\n- **Pectoralis major**: This muscle primarily acts on the humerus and does not prevent clavicle displacement.\r\n  \r\n- **Deltoid**: This muscle acts on the arm, specifically the humerus, and does not prevent clavicle displacement.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 144, 712.","responses":[{"text":"Sternocleidomastoid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Trapezius","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Deltoid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Subclavius","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pectoralis major","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16046,"text":"Which of the following nerves is damaged if the muscles of the anterior compartment of the arm are not functional?","explanation":"The musculocutaneous nerve arises from the lateral cord of the brachial plexus and is primarily responsible for innervating the muscles in the anterior compartment of the arm. These muscles include the biceps brachii, coracobrachialis, and brachialis. A lesion of the musculocutaneous nerve would result in the dysfunction of these muscles, affecting elbow flexion and forearm supination.\r\n\r\n#### Incorrect Options:\r\n\r\n- **Median nerve**: Primarily innervates the muscles of the anterior compartment of the forearm, not the arm.\r\n  \r\n- **Axillary nerve**: Innervates the deltoid and teres minor, which are not in the anterior compartment of the arm.\r\n  \r\n- **Radial nerve**: Primarily responsible for innervating the muscles in the posterior compartment of the arm and forearm.\r\n  \r\n- **Ulnar nerve**: Innervates some muscles in the forearm and hand but not the anterior compartment of the arm.","reference":"1)Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 686, 687.\r\n\r\n2)Desai SS, Arbor TC, Varacallo M. Anatomy, shoulder and upper limb, musculocutaneous nerve. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed June 13, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534199/","responses":[{"text":"Ulnar nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Median nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Axillary nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Musculocutaneous nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Radial nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16047,"text":"Which of the following muscles passes through the sulcus between the tubercles of the humerus?","explanation":"The long head of the bicep brachii originates from the supraglenoid tubercle and glenoid labrum of the scapula. It traverses the shoulder joint and passes through the intertubercular sulcus (also known as the bicipital groove) between the greater and lesser tubercles of the humerus. This anatomical feature allows it to act both as a shoulder and elbow joint flexor.\r\n\r\n#### Incorrect Options:\r\n\r\n- **Latissimus dorsi**: Primarily involved in shoulder extension and adduction, does not pass through the intertubercular sulcus.\r\n  \r\n- **Deltoid**: Primarily involved in arm abduction, does not pass through the intertubercular sulcus.\r\n  \r\n- **Coracobrachialis**: Helps in flexing and adducting the humerus, also does not pass through the intertubercular sulcus.\r\n  \r\n- **Pectoralis major**: Involved in adduction and medial rotation of the humerus, does not pass through the intertubercular sulcus.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 721.","responses":[{"text":"Coracobrachialis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pectoralis major","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Deltoid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Latissimus dorsi","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Long head of bicep brachii","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16049,"text":"Bursitis of which of the following extensor muscles of the forearm occurs in tennis players?","explanation":"This form of bursitis commonly affects tennis players and is a significant component of the condition known as \"tennis elbow\" or lateral epicondylitis. It is an inflammation of the bursa adjacent to the extensor carpi radialis brevis tendon, often caused by repetitive wrist extension motions typical in tennis strokes.\r\n\r\n#### Incorrect Options:\r\n\r\n- **Brachioradialis**: This muscle mainly aids in forearm flexion and pronation/supination, not commonly implicated in bursitis among tennis players.\r\n  \r\n- **Triceps brachii**: Primarily involved in elbow extension and not typically affected by bursitis in tennis players.\r\n  \r\n- **Brachialis**: Mainly involved in elbow flexion and also not commonly affected by bursitis in tennis.\r\n  \r\n- **Supinator**: Responsible for forearm supination and not typically involved in bursitis affecting tennis players.","reference":"1) Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 777.\r\n\r\n2) Buchanan BK, Varacallo M. Tennis elbow. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed June 12, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK431092/","responses":[{"text":"Triceps brachii","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Brachioradialis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Supinator","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Extensor carpi radialis brevis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Brachialis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16050,"text":"Bursitis of which of the following bursas occurs in housemaids?","explanation":"Prepatellar bursitis is inflammation of the prepatellar bursa, a small sac filled with lubricating fluid situated in front of the patella (kneecap). This condition is commonly seen in individuals who frequently kneel, such as housemaids, carpenters, and gardeners. It is colloquially known as \"Housemaid's Knee\" for this reason.\r\n\r\n#### Incorrect Options:\r\n\r\n- **Popliteal**: Also known as Baker's cyst, this is a different type of bursitis that occurs in the back of the knee joint.\r\n\r\n- **Pes anserinus**: Refers to a collective insertion of three tendons on the proximal medial side of the tibia, not a bursa affected in housemaids.\r\n  \r\n- **Medial collateral**: Refers to a ligament in the knee, not a bursa prone to inflammation in housemaids.\r\n  \r\n- **Infrapatellar**: This bursa is located below the patella and is not commonly associated with housemaids.","reference":"(1) Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 824.\r\n\r\n(2) Sato M, Watari T. Housemaid’s Knee (Prepatellar septic bursitis). Cureus. Accessed June 12, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7549991/","responses":[{"text":"Popliteal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pes anserinus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medial collateral","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Infrapatellar","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prepatellar","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16051,"text":"Fracture of midshaft of radius and ulna results in loss of which of the following movements in the forearm?","explanation":"A fracture of the midshaft of the radius and ulna is most likely to result in the loss of the ability to supinate and pronate the forearm. These movements are essential for various day-to-day activities and are dependent on the intact structure and functioning of both the radius and ulna.\r\n\r\n#### Incorrect Options:\r\n\r\n- **Flexion of wrist**: The wrist flexors are not primarily affected by a midshaft fracture of the radius and ulna.\r\n  \r\n- **Extension of wrist**: The wrist extensors are also not directly affected by such a fracture.\r\n  \r\n- **Flexion of fingers**: The flexors of the fingers are generally not affected by a midshaft fracture of the radius and ulna.\r\n\r\n- **Extension of fingers**: The extensors of the fingers are likewise not directly affected by this type of fracture.","reference":"Small RF, Taqi M, Yaish AM. Radius and ulnar shaft fractures. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed June 12, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557681/","responses":[{"text":"Supination and pronation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Extension of wrist","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Flexion of fingers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Flexion of wrist","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Extension of fingers","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16063,"text":"Which of the following is raised in bone remodeling?","explanation":"Bone alkaline phosphatase is an enzyme produced by osteoblasts and is elevated during periods of active bone remodeling. It serves as a biomarker for bone formation and is commonly used in the diagnosis and monitoring of diseases such as osteoporosis, Paget's disease, and other conditions involving bone turnover.\r\n\r\n#### Incorrect Options:\r\n\r\n- **Osteocalcin**: While it is also a marker for bone formation, it is not typically elevated during bone remodeling to the same extent as bone alkaline phosphatase.\r\n\r\n- **Procollagen 1**: This is a precursor molecule in collagen synthesis but is not specifically raised during bone remodeling.\r\n  \r\n- **Collagen**: It is the main structural protein in the extracellular matrix in various connective tissues but is not a marker for bone remodeling.\r\n  \r\n- **Procollagen 2**: Like procollagen 1, this is a precursor molecule in collagen synthesis but is not a specific marker for bone remodeling.","reference":"(1) Mescher AL, Junqueira LCU. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill; 2021: 141.\r\n\r\n(2) Tariq S, Tariq S, Lone KP, Khaliq S. Alkaline phosphatase is a predictor of Bone Mineral Density in postmenopausal females. Pakistan Journal of Medical Sciences. Published 2019. Accessed June 18, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6572960/","responses":[{"text":"Procollagen 2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Osteocalcin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Collagen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bone alkaline phosphatase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Procollagen 1","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16064,"text":"Which of the following vitamins is a cofactor of the lysyl hydroxylase enzyme?","explanation":"#### Ascorbic Acid\r\nAscorbic acid, also known as vitamin C, serves as a cofactor for the enzyme lysyl hydroxylase. This enzyme is involved in the hydroxylation of lysine residues in collagen, a critical step for stabilizing the collagen triple helix. A deficiency in ascorbic acid can lead to impaired collagen synthesis, as seen in conditions like scurvy.\r\n\r\n#### Incorrect Options:\r\n\r\n- **Thiamine**: Also known as Vitamin B1, is a cofactor for enzymes in carbohydrate metabolism but not for lysyl hydroxylase.\r\n  \r\n- **Pantothenate**: Involved in fatty acid synthesis and energy production, but not as a cofactor for lysyl hydroxylase.\r\n\r\n- **Riboflavin**: Also known as Vitamin B2, is a cofactor for various redox reactions but not for lysyl hydroxylase.\r\n\r\n- **Vitamin B6**: Involved in amino acid metabolism, but it is not a cofactor for lysyl hydroxylase.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 381.","responses":[{"text":"Pantothenate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Riboflavin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ascorbic acid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Thiamine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin B6","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16065,"text":"Which ligaments stabilize the knee joint during the back-and-forth motion?","explanation":"The cruciate ligaments, comprising the anterior cruciate ligament (ACL) and the posterior cruciate ligament (PCL), are crucial for stabilizing the knee joint during back-and-forth motions. They cross each other in the middle of the knee joint, and they control the anterior and posterior translation of the tibia relative to the femur.\r\n\r\n#### Incorrect Options:\r\n\r\n- **Menisci**: The menisci act as shock absorbers in the knee but do not primarily stabilize the knee during back-and-forth motion.\r\n\r\n- **Fibular collateral ligament**: Also known as the lateral collateral ligament (LCL), it stabilizes the knee against varus forces but not in back-and-forth motion.\r\n  \r\n- **Tibial collateral ligament**: Also known as the medial collateral ligament (MCL), it stabilizes the knee against valgus forces but not in back-and-forth motion.\r\n\r\n- **Patellar ligament**: This ligament extends from the patella to the tibial tuberosity and is primarily involved in knee extension.","reference":"(1) Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 576.\r\n\r\n(2) Gupton M, Imonugo O, Terreberry RR. Anatomy, bony pelvis and lower limb, knee. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed June 12, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK500017/","responses":[{"text":"Tibial collateral ligament","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Menisci","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibular collateral ligament","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cruciate ligaments","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Patellar ligament","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16066,"text":"Which of the following nerves is injured in a person with evert and dorsiflexed foot lacking the ability to flex his toes?","explanation":"The tibial nerve is a branch of the sciatic nerve and supplies the posterior compartment of the leg and the sole of the foot. It innervates muscles responsible for plantarflexion of the foot and flexion of the toes. A tibial nerve injury would result in the inability to flex the toes and might lead to an evert and dorsiflexed foot due to the unopposed action of muscles innervated by the opposing nerves.\r\n\r\n#### Incorrect Options:\r\n\r\n- **Saphenous nerve**: This nerve is a sensory nerve in the leg and does not control toe flexion or foot posture.\r\n  \r\n- **Plantar nerve**: The term is too general and typically refers to the medial and lateral plantar nerves, which are branches of the tibial nerve. However, it is the tibial nerve itself that would be responsible for the described symptoms.\r\n\r\n- **Deep peroneal nerve**: This nerve controls toe extension and dorsiflexion of the foot, not toe flexion.\r\n  \r\n- **Superficial peroneal nerve**: This nerve innervates the muscles responsible for foot eversion but does not control toe flexion.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 764.","responses":[{"text":"Tibial nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Saphenous nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plantar nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Deep peroneal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superficial peroneal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16067,"text":"Which of the following arteries provides nutrient artery to the fibula?","explanation":"The peroneal artery, also known as the fibular artery, is a branch of the posterior tibial artery. It travels along the medial side of the fibula and provides the nutrient artery to the fibula, supplying it with blood for its nourishment.\r\n\r\n#### Incorrect Options:\r\n\r\n- **Femoral artery**: This artery is situated in the upper leg and primarily supplies the thigh region, not the fibula.\r\n  \r\n- **Anterior tibial artery**: This artery supplies the anterior compartment of the leg and does not provide the nutrient artery to the fibula.\r\n\r\n- **Posterior tibial artery**: While the peroneal artery is a branch of the posterior tibial artery, it is not the posterior tibial artery itself that supplies the fibula.\r\n  \r\n- **Circumflex artery**: The term \"circumflex\" typically refers to arteries that curve around other structures but does not refer to the nutrient artery of the fibula.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 761.","responses":[{"text":"Posterior tibular artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Peroneal artery","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Circumflex artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior tibular artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Femoral artery","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16087,"text":"Vitamin D synthesis takes place by the action of UV on which of the following molecules?","explanation":"### Explanation for MCQ on Vitamin D Synthesis\r\n\r\nThe correct answer is **Cholesterol**.\r\n\r\n#### Cholesterol\r\nVitamin D synthesis occurs in the skin, where ultraviolet B (UVB) rays from the sun convert 7-dehydrocholesterol, a molecule derived from cholesterol, into cholecalciferol (Vitamin D3). This is subsequently converted to its active form, calcitriol, in the liver and kidneys.\r\n\r\n#### Incorrect Options:\r\n\r\n- **Fatty acids**: These are not involved in Vitamin D synthesis.\r\n  \r\n- **Triglycerides**: These are a form of lipid storage but are not directly involved in Vitamin D synthesis.\r\n  \r\n- **LDL (Low-Density Lipoprotein)**: While LDL does carry cholesterol, it is not the cholesterol in LDL that is directly converted to Vitamin D.\r\n  \r\n- **HDL (High-Density Lipoprotein)**: HDL is involved in cholesterol transport but is not directly involved in Vitamin D synthesis.","reference":"(1) Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 390.\r\n\r\n(2) Bikle DD, Feingold KR, Anawalt B, et al. Vitamin d: production, metabolism and mechanisms of action. Endotext. Published 2000. Accessed June 12, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK278935/","responses":[{"text":"HDL","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"LDL","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Triglycerides","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cholesterol","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Fatty acids","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16088,"text":"Which of the following cells are present in the Howship's lacunae?","explanation":"#### Osteoclasts\r\nHowship's lacunae, also known as resorption lacunae, are tiny depressions seen on the bone surface where bone resorption occurs. Osteoclasts are the cells responsible for this bone resorption and are found in these Howship's lacunae. They release enzymes and acids that dissolve the mineralized matrix, thereby facilitating bone remodeling.\r\n\r\n#### Incorrect Options:\r\n\r\n- **Chondroblasts**: These cells are responsible for producing cartilage and are not found in Howship's lacunae.\r\n\r\n- **Osteoblasts**: These cells are involved in bone formation, not resorption. They are not found in Howship's lacunae but are commonly found in regions undergoing ossification.\r\n  \r\n- **Osteocytes**: These are mature bone cells entombed in the bone matrix and are not found in Howship's lacunae.\r\n  \r\n- **Chondrocytes**: These are cells found in cartilage and are not involved in bone resorption.","reference":"Mescher AL, Junqueira LCU. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill; 2021: 143.","responses":[{"text":"Osteocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chondrocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chondroblasts","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Osteoblasts","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Osteoclasts","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16089,"text":"Which of the following ions's membrane permeability is closest to resting membrane potential?","explanation":"#### Potassium (K)\r\nIn a cell at rest, the resting membrane potential is primarily determined by the concentration gradient of potassium ions (K+) and their permeability across the membrane. K+ ions have a high permeability when the cell membrane is at rest, allowing them to freely move across the membrane. This creates a potential close to the equilibrium potential for potassium, which is typically around -70 mV to -85 mV depending on the cell type.\r\n\r\n#### Investigations\r\nIn clinical contexts, disturbances in resting membrane potential may be evaluated using:\r\n- Electrocardiography (ECG) for cardiac cells\r\n- Electromyography (EMG) for muscle cells\r\n- Blood tests to measure ion levels\r\n\r\n#### Management\r\n1. **Non-pharmacological**: Dietary modifications to maintain proper ion balance.\r\n2. **Pharmacological**: Drugs that modify ion channel function may be prescribed in certain conditions affecting membrane potentials.\r\n3. **Surgical**: Not applicable for direct management of resting membrane potential.\r\n\r\n#### Incorrect Options:\r\n\r\n- **Na (Sodium)**: Sodium ions also contribute to the resting membrane potential, but their permeability is much lower compared to potassium ions.\r\n\r\n- **Ca (Calcium)**: Calcium ions play a significant role in cellular processes such as muscle contraction but are not the primary determinant of the resting membrane potential.\r\n\r\n- **Cl (Chloride)**: Chloride ions generally follow the movement of other ions but are not the main contributors to the resting membrane potential.\r\n\r\n- **HCO3 (Bicarbonate)**: Bicarbonate ions are more involved in acid-base balance and not directly related to resting membrane potential.","reference":"Chrysafides SM, Bordes SJ, Sharma S. Physiology, resting potential. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed June 12, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538338/","responses":[{"text":"K","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Na","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HCO3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ca","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cl","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16090,"text":"Which of the following proteins binds to calcium ions during action potential to release calcium from the sarcoplasmic reticulum?","explanation":"Troponin C is a calcium-binding protein that is part of the troponin complex in skeletal and cardiac muscle cells. During an action potential, calcium ions released from the sarcoplasmic reticulum bind to Troponin C. This binding event triggers a conformational change in the troponin-tropomyosin complex, which in turn exposes the myosin-binding sites on actin filaments and initiates muscle contraction.\r\n\r\n#### Incorrect Options:\r\n\r\n- **Troponin T**: This component of the troponin complex is responsible for binding the complex to tropomyosin but does not bind calcium ions.\r\n\r\n- **Troponin I**: This protein inhibits the actin-myosin interaction and is also part of the troponin complex, but it does not bind to calcium ions.\r\n\r\n- **Titin**: This is a large protein that acts like a spring and provides structural integrity to the sarcomere. It does not bind to calcium ions.\r\n\r\n- **Fibronectin**: This is an extracellular matrix protein that plays a key role in cell adhesion and migration but is not involved in muscle contraction or calcium ion binding.","reference":"(1) Mescher AL, Junqueira LCU. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill; 2021: 197.\r\n\r\n(2) Kuo IY, Ehrlich BE. Signaling in muscle contraction. Cold Spring Harbor Perspectives in Biology. Published February 2015. Accessed June 12, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4315934/","responses":[{"text":"Fibronectin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Titin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Troponin C","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Troponin I","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Troponin T","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16092,"text":"Which of the following proteins inhibits the attachment of myosin cross-bridges with actin?","explanation":"#### Tropomyosin\r\nTropomyosin is a protein that wraps around actin filaments in muscle cells and serves to block the myosin-binding sites on actin. In a relaxed muscle, tropomyosin inhibits the attachment of myosin cross-bridges with actin. During muscle contraction, calcium ions bind to troponin, causing a conformational change that moves tropomyosin away from the myosin-binding sites on actin, thereby allowing the cross-bridges to form.\r\n\r\n#### Investigations\r\nTo evaluate muscle function or dysfunction, the following investigations could be considered:\r\n- Electromyography (EMG)\r\n- Muscle biopsy for histological analysis\r\n\r\n#### Management\r\n1. **Non-pharmacological**: Physical therapy, muscle-strengthening exercises.\r\n2. **Pharmacological**: Medications to improve muscle tone or function, depending on the underlying condition.\r\n3. **Surgical**: Procedures may be undertaken to correct anatomical issues affecting muscle function.\r\n\r\n#### Incorrect Options:\r\n\r\n- **Phosphalamban**: This protein is found in cardiac muscle and modulates calcium uptake into the sarcoplasmic reticulum but does not inhibit myosin-actin interaction.\r\n\r\n- **Calmodulin**: This is a calcium-binding protein that interacts with other proteins to mediate various cellular processes, including muscle contraction, but it doesn't directly inhibit myosin-actin interaction.\r\n  \r\n- **Titin**: This is the largest known protein and serves primarily as a molecular spring in sarcomeres to maintain structural integrity. It does not inhibit myosin-actin interaction.\r\n  \r\n- **Troponin**: Although troponin plays a role in regulating muscle contraction, it does so by moving tropomyosin away from the binding sites when calcium binds to it. It does not inhibit the attachment itself.","reference":"Schevzov G, Whittaker SP, Fath T, Lin JJ, Gunning PW. Tropomyosin isoforms and reagents. Bioarchitecture. Published 2011. Accessed June 12, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3210517/","responses":[{"text":"Tropomyosin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Calmodulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Troponin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phosphalamban","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Titin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16093,"text":"Which of the following participates in maintaining the medial longitudinal arch?","explanation":"#### Spring Ligament\r\nThe Spring ligament, also known as the plantar calcaneonavicular ligament, plays a crucial role in maintaining the medial longitudinal arch of the foot. This ligament connects the calcaneus to the navicular bone and provides support to the head of the talus, thereby supporting the arch.\r\n\r\n#### Investigations\r\nFor diagnosing issues related to the medial longitudinal arch, the following investigations may be considered:\r\n- Radiography (weight-bearing views)\r\n- MRI for ligament assessment\r\n\r\n#### Management\r\n1. **Non-pharmacological**: Orthotic insoles, foot arch supports.\r\n2. **Pharmacological**: NSAIDs for pain control.\r\n3. **Surgical**: Reconstruction or repair of damaged ligaments may be considered in severe cases.\r\n\r\n#### Incorrect Options:\r\n\r\n- **Calcaneocuboid Ligament**: This ligament stabilizes the calcaneocuboid joint but is not directly involved in maintaining the medial longitudinal arch.\r\n  \r\n- **Talofibular Ligament**: This ligament stabilizes the talofibular joint, part of the ankle joint, and does not contribute to the medial longitudinal arch.\r\n  \r\n- **Talocalcaneal Ligament**: Also known as the talocalcaneal interosseous ligament, it stabilizes the subtalar joint but is not primarily involved in maintaining the medial longitudinal arch.\r\n  \r\n- **Deltoid Ligament**: This is a strong ligament that stabilizes the medial aspect of the ankle joint, not the medial longitudinal arch of the foot.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 638.","responses":[{"text":"Talo fibular ligament","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calceneocuboid ligament","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spring ligament","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Deltoid ligament","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Talo calcaneal ligament","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16094,"text":"A woman visited the neurology outpatient department with the complaint of burning pain, and pins and needles sensation in the lateral three and a half digits. On examination, the physician also noticed weakness in the thenar muscles. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"#### Carpal Tunnel Syndrome\r\nThe symptoms described—burning pain and pins-and-needles sensation in the lateral three and a half digits, along with weakness in the thenar muscles—are classic indicators of carpal tunnel syndrome. This condition occurs due to compression of the median nerve as it passes through the carpal tunnel in the wrist. The median nerve supplies sensation to the lateral three and a half fingers (thumb, index, middle, and lateral half of the ring finger) and innervates the thenar muscles responsible for thumb movements. \r\n\r\n#### Investigations\r\nFor definitive diagnosis and management, the following investigations are commonly ordered:\r\n- Electromyography (EMG)\r\n- Nerve conduction studies\r\n\r\n#### Management\r\n1. **Non-pharmacological**: Wrist splinting, activity modification, and ergonomic improvements.\r\n2. **Pharmacological**: Nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) for pain control.\r\n3. **Surgical**: Carpal tunnel release surgery is considered for severe or refractory cases.\r\n\r\n#### Incorrect Options:\r\n  \r\n- **Dupuytren Contracture**: This condition involves the palmar fascia and results in contracture of the fingers but does not cause the specific neurological symptoms described.\r\n\r\n- **Tenosynovitis**: Inflammation of the tendon sheath may cause pain but does not typically produce the characteristic symptoms of median nerve compression.\r\n  \r\n- **Trigger Finger**: This condition involves the locking or catching of the fingers and does not present with symptoms of nerve compression.\r\n\r\n- **Tennis Elbow**: This affects the lateral epicondyle of the humerus and involves the extensor muscles of the forearm, not the hand or digits.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 789.","responses":[{"text":"Tennis elbow","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tenosynovitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dupuytren contracture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carpal Tunnel syndrome","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Trigger finger","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16121,"text":"Which of the following muscles have the same innervation as the lumbricals?","explanation":"#### Digitorum Profundus\r\nThe lumbricals and the digitorum profundus muscle share the same innervation sources, which are the median and ulnar nerves. Specifically, the lumbricals of the first and second digits are innervated by the median nerve, while those of the third and fourth digits are innervated by the ulnar nerve. Similarly, the medial half of digitorum profundus (serving the 4th and 5th digits) is innervated by the ulnar nerve, and the lateral half (serving the 2nd and 3rd digits) is innervated by the median nerve.\r\n\r\n#### Incorrect Options:\r\n\r\n- **Pronator Quadratus**: This muscle pronates the forearm and is solely innervated by the anterior interosseous nerve, a branch of the median nerve. It doesn't share the same innervation as the lumbricals.\r\n\r\n- **Flexor Carpis**: This option likely refers to either flexor carpi radialis or flexor carpi ulnaris. Both are wrist flexors but are not innervated by the same nerves as the lumbricals. Flexor carpi radialis is innervated by the median nerve, while flexor carpi ulnaris is innervated by the ulnar nerve.\r\n\r\n- **Pollicis Longus**: There are two muscles with similar names, the extensor pollicis longus and the flexor pollicis longus, and neither shares the same innervation pattern as the lumbricals.\r\n\r\n- **Thenar**: The thenar muscles (abductor pollicis brevis, flexor pollicis brevis, and opponens pollicis) are innervated by the recurrent branch of the median nerve and do not share the same innervation as the lumbricals.","reference":"(1) Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 734.\r\n\r\n(2) Valenzuela M, Varacallo M. Anatomy, shoulder and upper limb, hand lumbrical muscles. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed June 12, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534876/","responses":[{"text":"Digitorum profundus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pronator quadratus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pollicis longus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Flexor carpis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thenar","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16122,"text":"Medial and lateral plantar nerves enter the leg by passing deep to which of the following structures?","explanation":"#### Abductor Hallucis\r\nThe medial and lateral plantar nerves are branches of the tibial nerve. They supply the plantar surface of the foot and are key to its sensory and motor functions. These nerves enter the sole of the foot by passing deep to the abductor hallucis muscle. The abductor hallucis muscle itself is responsible for the abduction of the great toe, and its position in the foot makes it the structure that the medial and lateral plantar nerves have to navigate past.\r\n\r\n#### Incorrect Options:\r\n\r\n- **Flexor Hallucis Longus**: This muscle is located more posteriorly in the leg and is responsible for flexing the great toe. It is not the structure the plantar nerves pass deep to.\r\n\r\n- **Tibialis Posterior**: This muscle is in the deep posterior compartment of the leg and its primary functions include plantarflexion and inversion of the foot. Again, the plantar nerves do not pass deep to this muscle to enter the foot.\r\n\r\n- **Digitorum Longus**: This muscle aids in toe flexion but is also not the anatomical structure that the plantar nerves pass deep to.\r\n\r\n- **Rectus Femoris**: This muscle is a part of the quadriceps group and is located in the thigh, far removed from the course of the plantar nerves in the foot.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 656.","responses":[{"text":"Flexor hallucis longus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Abductor hallucis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Tibialis posterior","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rectus femoris","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Digitorum longus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16123,"text":"Which of the following muscles passes through the sulcus between the tubercles in the humerus?","explanation":"#### Biceps Brachii\r\nThe biceps brachii muscle passes through the sulcus (groove) between the greater and lesser tubercles of the humerus. This groove is also known as the intertubercular groove or the bicipital groove. The long head of the biceps brachii originates from the supraglenoid tubercle of the scapula and runs through this groove, allowing it to act as both a shoulder and elbow flexor.\r\n\r\n#### Incorrect Options:\r\n\r\n- **Brachialis**: This muscle is situated underneath the biceps brachii and is primarily an elbow flexor. It does not pass through the sulcus between the tubercles of the humerus.\r\n  \r\n- **Anconeus**: This small muscle assists the triceps in extending the elbow and is located near the elbow, not the humerus' tubercles.\r\n  \r\n- **Coracobrachialis**: Originating from the coracoid process of the scapula, this muscle also does not pass through the sulcus between the tubercles of the humerus. It acts as a shoulder flexor and adductor.\r\n  \r\n- **Triceps Brachii**: This muscle is an extensor of the elbow and does not pass through the sulcus between the tubercles of the humerus.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 721.","responses":[{"text":"Anconeus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Biceps brachii","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Coracobrachialis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Triceps brachii","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Brachialis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16124,"text":"Calcium binds to which of the following molecules after being released from the endoplasmic reticulum?","explanation":"#### Troponin C\r\nIn the context of muscle contraction, calcium ions (Ca2+) play a crucial role after being released from the sarcoplasmic reticulum (a specialized form of endoplasmic reticulum). Calcium ions specifically bind to Troponin C, which is a component of the troponin complex located on the thin filament of the myofibril. Upon binding to calcium, Troponin C undergoes a conformational change that allows the entire troponin-tropomyosin complex to move, thereby exposing the myosin-binding sites on actin. This facilitates the cross-bridge formation between actin and myosin, enabling muscle contraction.\r\n\r\n#### Incorrect Options:\r\n\r\n- **Myosin**: Calcium does not directly bind to myosin. Myosin interacts with actin to facilitate muscle contraction, but this interaction is regulated by the calcium-binding to Troponin C.\r\n\r\n- **Troponin I**: This is another component of the troponin complex, but its role is to inhibit the actin-myosin interaction in the absence of calcium. It does not bind calcium itself.\r\n\r\n- **Tropomyosin**: This is the protein that covers the myosin-binding sites on actin in relaxed muscle. While it is affected by the calcium-binding to Troponin C, it is not the molecule that calcium binds to directly.\r\n\r\n- **Troponin T**: This component of the troponin complex binds to tropomyosin, helping to anchor the troponin complex to the thin filament. It is not the site of calcium binding.","reference":"(1) Mescher AL, Junqueira LCU. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill; 2021: 197.\r\n\r\n(2) WAKABAYASHI T. Mechanism of the calcium-regulation of muscle contraction — In pursuit of its structural basis —. Proceedings of the Japan Academy. Series B, Physical and Biological Sciences. Published July 21, 2015. Accessed June 12, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4631897/","responses":[{"text":"Troponin I","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Troponin C","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Myosin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Troponin T","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tropomyosin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16125,"text":"What is it called when diffusion potential across the membrane that exactly opposes the net diffusion of particular ions?","explanation":"#### Equilibrium Potential\r\nThe term \"equilibrium potential\" refers to the diffusion potential across the membrane that exactly opposes the net diffusion of a particular ion. In other words, at this potential, the electrochemical driving forces acting on that ion are balanced. No net movement of the ion occurs across the membrane because the chemical and electrical forces are equal but opposite. The equilibrium potential is a critical concept in understanding neuronal function and signal transduction.\r\n\r\n#### Incorrect Options:\r\n\r\n- **Resting Membrane Potential**: This is the membrane potential of a cell at rest and not undergoing any form of electrical signaling. While it is influenced by the equilibrium potentials of various ions, it is not the same thing as equilibrium potential.\r\n\r\n- **Liquid Junction Potential**: This term refers to the potential difference that occurs when two different solutions are in contact, often in the context of electrophysiological experiments. It is not related to the diffusion potential that opposes ion movement.\r\n\r\n- **Diffusion Potential**: This is a more generic term that refers to the potential difference generated across a membrane because of a concentration difference. It is a component of the driving force for ion movement but is not specifically the potential that \"exactly opposes\" the ion's net diffusion.\r\n\r\n- **Electrical Potential**: This is a broad term that refers to the potential energy per unit charge associated with any electric field. While the equilibrium potential is a form of electrical potential, the term by itself is too general for this specific context.","reference":"Chrysafides SM, Bordes SJ, Sharma S. Physiology, resting potential. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed June 18, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538338/","responses":[{"text":"Diffusion potential","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Equilibrium potential","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Resting membrane potential","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Liquid junction potential","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Electrical potential","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16126,"text":"Which of the following hormones is involved in maintaining the calcium and phosphorus metabolism?","explanation":"Parathyroid hormone (PTH) is primarily responsible for maintaining calcium and phosphorus metabolism. PTH is produced by the parathyroid glands, located adjacent to the thyroid gland. When serum calcium levels are low, PTH is released. Its effects include:\r\n\r\n1. **Increasing calcium reabsorption** in the kidneys\r\n2. **Promoting calcium release** from bone resorption\r\n3. **Enhancing calcium absorption** in the gastrointestinal tract indirectly through the activation of vitamin D\r\n4. **Phosphorus excretion** in urine to maintain the calcium-phosphorus balance\r\n\r\nThese functions together help elevate the serum calcium levels and control phosphorus metabolism, making PTH critical for calcium homeostasis.\r\n\r\n#### Incorrect Options:\r\n\r\n- **Insulin**: While insulin is essential for glucose metabolism, it doesn't have a direct role in maintaining calcium and phosphorus metabolism.\r\n  \r\n- **Calcitonin**: This hormone does have a role in calcium metabolism but mainly opposes the action of PTH. It promotes bone formation and decreases blood calcium levels, so it wouldn't be considered a hormone that 'maintains' calcium and phosphorus metabolism in the sense required by the question.\r\n  \r\n- **Cortisol**: Cortisol is a glucocorticoid hormone produced by the adrenal glands. It is involved in stress response, metabolism, and immune response, but not directly in calcium and phosphorus metabolism.\r\n  \r\n- **Thyroid Hormone**: Although thyroid hormones affect almost every physiological process, including metabolism, they are not specifically involved in calcium and phosphorus metabolism.","reference":"Khan M, Jose A, Sharma S. Physiology, parathyroid hormone. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed June 11, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK499940/","responses":[{"text":"Calcitonin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cortisol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Insulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Parathyroid hormone","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Thyroid hormone","correct":false,"visible":false}]}
]

